<i>To begin with, all</i>
<i>the incidents and characters in this story...</i>

3
00:01:18,845 --> 00:01:20,836
<i>might be fictitious...</i>

4
00:01:20,914 --> 00:01:23,212
<i>and any resemblance</i>
<i>to you or me...</i>

5
00:01:23,283 --> 00:01:26,013
<i>might be purely coincidental.</i>

6
00:01:26,086 --> 00:01:28,111
<i>The name of the town</i>
<i>isn't important.</i>

7
00:01:28,188 --> 00:01:30,622
<i>It's the one that's just</i>
<i>28 minutes from the big city...</i>

8
00:01:30,690 --> 00:01:33,318
<i>23 if you catch</i>
<i>the Morning Express.</i>

9
00:01:33,393 --> 00:01:37,295
<i>It's on a river, and it's got houses</i>
<i>and stores and churches...</i>

10
00:01:37,363 --> 00:01:39,456
<i>and a Main Street.</i>

11
00:01:39,532 --> 00:01:41,693
<i>Nothing fancy</i>
<i>like Broadway or Market.</i>

12
00:01:41,768 --> 00:01:43,793
<i>Just plain Main.</i>

13
00:01:43,870 --> 00:01:45,861
<i>Drugs, dry goods, shoes...</i>

14
00:01:45,939 --> 00:01:50,205
<i>those horrible little chain stores</i>
<i>that breed like rabbits.</i>

15
00:01:50,276 --> 00:01:53,973
<i>Also a street for the upper,</i>
<i>the exclusive of the town...</i>

16
00:01:54,047 --> 00:01:57,505
<i>where the country-club set live</i>
<i>when they're not at the country club.</i>

17
00:01:57,584 --> 00:02:00,417
<i>This is the first Saturday in May...</i>

18
00:02:00,487 --> 00:02:04,389
<i>and tonight the first dinner dance</i>
<i>of the country-club season.</i>

19
00:02:06,759 --> 00:02:10,217
<i>Well, anyway, this house belongs to</i>
<i>Brad and Deborah Bishop...</i>

20
00:02:10,296 --> 00:02:12,662
<i>two of my dearest friends.</i>

21
00:02:12,732 --> 00:02:15,428
<i>Brad bought this house</i>
<i>before he went to war.</i>

22
00:02:15,502 --> 00:02:18,266
<i>It was Brad who gave me</i>
<i>my first black eye and...</i>

23
00:02:18,338 --> 00:02:21,068
<i>and my first kiss.</i>

24
00:02:21,141 --> 00:02:25,635
<i>Well, when he came home from the war,</i>
<i>he came home with a wife... Deborah.</i>

25
00:02:30,316 --> 00:02:33,774
Thomasino said to tell you
he found room for your briefcase in the bag.

26
00:02:33,853 --> 00:02:36,083
Good for Thomasino.

27
00:02:36,156 --> 00:02:39,523
- Why'd you have him pack a bag?
- Because I know these Saturday conferences.

28
00:02:39,592 --> 00:02:43,187
A bit like Saturday poker games...
don't plan on doing anything Sunday.

29
00:02:43,263 --> 00:02:46,721
It's strange, your not letting me know
when you plan to be away overnight.

30
00:02:46,799 --> 00:02:50,257
This is just in case, darling.
There's no telling how late it'll be.

31
00:02:50,336 --> 00:02:54,102
And I like my own pajamas between me
and the sheets in a Turkish bath.

32
00:02:54,174 --> 00:02:56,404
You'll phone this afternoon,
though, either way, won't you?

33
00:02:56,476 --> 00:02:58,535
And leave word,
even if I'm not here?

34
00:02:58,611 --> 00:03:00,602
Just where might you be
when I call if not here?

35
00:03:00,680 --> 00:03:03,205
First Saturday in May, remember?
The Settlement House Picnic.

36
00:03:03,283 --> 00:03:05,717
That's right. The Women's Club thing.
Like it?

37
00:03:05,785 --> 00:03:07,980
Anything to do with kids.
You know that.

38
00:03:08,054 --> 00:03:10,488
What are you wearing tonight?

39
00:03:10,557 --> 00:03:12,787
I've got the one
you liked so much in <i>Vogue.</i>

40
00:03:12,859 --> 00:03:15,726
- But if you're staying in town...
- What color?

41
00:03:15,795 --> 00:03:18,958
Black, like you said.
Brad, I don't want to go without you.

42
00:03:19,032 --> 00:03:21,057
Darling, it's the first
dinner dance of the season.

43
00:03:21,134 --> 00:03:23,967
- If I only knew you were gonna be there.
- I will be if I can...

44
00:03:24,037 --> 00:03:26,335
and if I can't, why should
that throw you into a panic?

45
00:03:26,406 --> 00:03:28,897
What are you afraid of,
anyway, Deborah?

46
00:03:30,476 --> 00:03:32,671
- Good morning, Thomasino.
- Morning, Mr. Bishop.

47
00:03:35,315 --> 00:03:37,340
I'm not in a panic.

48
00:03:37,417 --> 00:03:40,079
Well, then?

49
00:03:40,153 --> 00:03:43,919
It's just that suddenly the thought
of going to that dance tonight without you...

50
00:03:48,928 --> 00:03:51,590
- Brad?
<i>- Hmm?</i>

51
00:03:51,664 --> 00:03:54,929
Addie Ross... she used to be
sort of your ideal, wasn't she?

52
00:03:55,001 --> 00:03:57,196
Now how did Addie
get into this conversation?

53
00:03:57,270 --> 00:04:01,104
I never knew you read <i>Vogue.</i>
I never thought men bothered much about it.

54
00:04:01,174 --> 00:04:04,871
What's <i>Vogue</i> got to do with it? I told you
I picked it up on the train coming home one night.

55
00:04:04,944 --> 00:04:07,208
- Some woman had left it behind.
- Some woman.

56
00:04:07,280 --> 00:04:11,046
<i>Yes, some woman. I thumbed through it and</i>
<i>saw a dress I thought would look smart on you.</i>

57
00:04:11,117 --> 00:04:13,347
What's wrong with that?

58
00:04:13,419 --> 00:04:15,649
Nothing, I guess.
Nothing at all.

59
00:04:15,722 --> 00:04:18,987
- I should hope not.
- Well, I've gotta pick up Rita.

60
00:04:19,058 --> 00:04:21,686
- You'll phone about tonight, won't you?
- I told you I would.

61
00:04:24,264 --> 00:04:26,391
It just so happens
that the dress I bought...

62
00:04:26,466 --> 00:04:29,128
that you picked out of <i>Vogue</i> that some
woman happened to leave on the train...

63
00:04:29,202 --> 00:04:32,933
is exactly the dress that Addie Ross
wore to the concert two weeks ago!

64
00:04:37,110 --> 00:04:39,135
Hot toast, Mr. Bishop.

65
00:04:44,884 --> 00:04:48,843
<i> She won't stay mad</i>
<i>at him long. She's too much in love.</i>

66
00:04:48,921 --> 00:04:51,219
<i>Pretty soon,</i>
<i>she'll be full of self-reproach.</i>

67
00:04:51,291 --> 00:04:55,250
<i>Women are so silly.</i>

68
00:04:55,628 --> 00:04:58,529
<i>Now, this is that street where people</i>
<i>on the way up and on the way down...</i>

69
00:04:58,598 --> 00:05:00,828
<i>live alongside each other for awhile.</i>

70
00:05:00,900 --> 00:05:02,993
<i>Rita and George Phipps</i>
<i>are on their way up...</i>

71
00:05:03,069 --> 00:05:05,060
<i>that is, if Rita has her way.</i>

72
00:05:05,138 --> 00:05:07,936
<i>And that's the only way</i>
<i>she'll have any part of, thank you.</i>

73
00:05:08,007 --> 00:05:11,499
<i>There she is now.</i>
<i>Ready, waiting. That's Rita.</i>

74
00:05:16,115 --> 00:05:18,106
Hi. You're late.
I won't be a minute.

75
00:05:18,184 --> 00:05:21,312
Just one last look at the twins
and I've gotta give Sadie her check.

76
00:05:29,662 --> 00:05:31,892
On behalf of the underprivileged
children of this town...

77
00:05:31,964 --> 00:05:33,955
I'd like to thank you
over-privileged ladies...

78
00:05:34,033 --> 00:05:36,194
for sharing your
excess privileges with us.

79
00:05:36,269 --> 00:05:38,965
There's something odd-looking
about you today, George.

80
00:05:39,038 --> 00:05:41,768
Just that usual two-headed
schoolteacher look.

81
00:05:41,841 --> 00:05:44,639
You're all dressed up. Saturday,
no school, and you're all dressed up.

82
00:05:44,711 --> 00:05:47,043
Just my little old blue serge.

83
00:05:47,113 --> 00:05:51,641
First Saturday of trout season. Brad says
ever since you were big enough lift a fish...

84
00:05:51,718 --> 00:05:54,050
Shh. Listen closely.

85
00:05:54,120 --> 00:05:58,147
Can you hear the grateful murmur of the trout
as they whisper in the brooks and streams?

86
00:05:58,224 --> 00:06:01,716
This is what they whisper:
"Phipps will not fish today."

87
00:06:01,794 --> 00:06:03,989
Mm. You're cute. But why?

88
00:06:05,631 --> 00:06:08,498
Because I've got
something better to do.

89
00:06:08,568 --> 00:06:10,593
Have a nice day.

90
00:06:15,508 --> 00:06:19,774
Debby, darling, we'll have to stop station.
I've just got to get my copy off on the 8:42.

91
00:06:19,846 --> 00:06:21,973
Do you mind?

92
00:06:26,352 --> 00:06:29,412
What's George
being so mysterious about?

93
00:06:29,489 --> 00:06:31,980
I wouldn't know.
It seems we're not talking.

94
00:06:32,058 --> 00:06:34,117
- Oh, I'm sorry.
- Oh, it's just one of those things.

95
00:06:34,193 --> 00:06:37,492
It'll be all right.
Why? Was he acting strangely?

96
00:06:37,563 --> 00:06:41,966
Mm. Not exactly. Well, it's only he's
not going fishing and being all dressed up.

97
00:06:42,034 --> 00:06:44,867
All dressed up?

98
00:06:44,937 --> 00:06:47,667
Why, so he is. His blue suit.

99
00:06:47,740 --> 00:06:52,143
On Saturday of all things.
And no fishing. Hmm.

100
00:06:52,211 --> 00:06:54,771
The radio hasn't been fixed yet.

101
00:06:54,847 --> 00:06:57,816
Oh. And they've just
gone on the air.

102
00:06:57,884 --> 00:07:01,547
Oh, well. Save myself listening
to the murder of my little brainchild.

103
00:07:01,621 --> 00:07:05,113
Rita, why on earth do you do it?
Five of those radio programs every week.

104
00:07:05,191 --> 00:07:07,182
Up until dawn
almost every night.

105
00:07:07,260 --> 00:07:09,990
Because each week
I receive in return 100 pieces...

106
00:07:10,062 --> 00:07:13,122
of what Addie Ross calls
"the most restful shade of green in the worid."

107
00:07:13,199 --> 00:07:15,190
Unquote. Addie again.

108
00:07:15,268 --> 00:07:18,237
Why is it that sooner or later,
no matter what we talk about...

109
00:07:18,304 --> 00:07:20,738
we wind up talking
about Addie Ross?

110
00:07:20,807 --> 00:07:23,469
<i> Maybe it's because</i>
<i>if you giris didn't talk about me...</i>

111
00:07:23,543 --> 00:07:25,534
<i>you just wouldn't talk at all.</i>

112
00:07:25,611 --> 00:07:28,478
<i>That's right. I'm Addie.</i>

113
00:07:28,548 --> 00:07:31,176
<i>I'm the one theyjust</i>
<i>can't help talking about.</i>

114
00:07:31,250 --> 00:07:33,878
<i>My very dearest friends too.</i>

115
00:07:33,953 --> 00:07:37,753
You know, I wonder if she knows
how much we do talk about her.

116
00:07:37,824 --> 00:07:40,156
And what we say
and how we feel about her.

117
00:07:40,226 --> 00:07:42,751
<i>I know. Believe me, I do.</i>

118
00:07:42,829 --> 00:07:44,854
<i>And it doesn't matter.</i>

119
00:07:44,931 --> 00:07:48,958
<i>It doesn't matter nearly as much</i>
<i>as what all of you don't know... yet.</i>

120
00:08:14,193 --> 00:08:16,923
<i>- Morning, Mrs. Hollingsway.</i>
- Haven't the others gotten here yet?

121
00:08:16,996 --> 00:08:19,226
No. You're the very first,
the early bird.

122
00:08:19,298 --> 00:08:22,893
- I've taken it upon myself
to get the children aboard.
- Oh. Good idea, Miss Hawkins.

123
00:08:22,969 --> 00:08:25,802
So that when the other ladies arrive,
we'll be all ready to go.

124
00:08:25,872 --> 00:08:27,965
Fine. If they'll only get here.

125
00:08:36,716 --> 00:08:39,378
Oh, I'm sorry we're late.
Rita had to go by the station.

126
00:08:39,452 --> 00:08:41,443
Oh, sure.
See anyone there you know?

127
00:08:41,521 --> 00:08:44,979
- Just a husband of mine running like mad. Why?
- Nobody else?

128
00:08:45,057 --> 00:08:47,150
Where's Addie? Weren't you
supposed to pick her up?

129
00:08:47,226 --> 00:08:49,387
Nothing's happened to her,
I hope.

130
00:08:49,462 --> 00:08:52,488
Addie Ross left town this morning.

131
00:08:52,565 --> 00:08:54,897
Left town?

132
00:08:54,967 --> 00:08:56,901
Well, what do you mean, "left town"?

133
00:08:56,969 --> 00:08:59,403
She certainly could've told someone,
at least phoned.

134
00:08:59,472 --> 00:09:03,340
- She's left for good.
- Then it must've been something
sudden, some emergency.

135
00:09:03,409 --> 00:09:05,843
What makes you so sure it's for good?
How do you know?

136
00:09:05,912 --> 00:09:08,574
Well, the doorman told me
she subleased her apartment last week...

137
00:09:08,648 --> 00:09:10,639
and yesterday she sold her car.

138
00:09:10,716 --> 00:09:12,980
So much for
your sudden emergency.

139
00:09:13,052 --> 00:09:17,148
If that isn't just like her. Why do you suppose
she had to keep it such a big secret?

140
00:09:17,223 --> 00:09:20,283
Who knows why Addie does
or doesn't do anything?

141
00:09:30,336 --> 00:09:33,999
I've got a letter for the Mesdames Bishop,
Hollingsway and Phipps.

142
00:09:34,073 --> 00:09:36,507
From the dear departed, I'll bet.

143
00:09:36,576 --> 00:09:39,841
Addie's so tactful.
She even puts us in alphabetical order.

144
00:09:42,214 --> 00:09:44,648
- Open it up.
- No, let's wait.

145
00:09:44,717 --> 00:09:47,015
- For what?
- Till we get back. Knowing Addie...

146
00:09:47,086 --> 00:09:49,213
I mean, why let her spoil our day?

147
00:09:49,288 --> 00:09:53,520
Not my day. Addie Ross never
saw the day she could spoil my day.

148
00:09:53,593 --> 00:09:55,686
Did I put enough days into that?

149
00:09:57,897 --> 00:10:00,991
<i>Dearest Debby, Lora Mae and Rita.</i>

150
00:10:01,067 --> 00:10:04,867
<i>As you know by now, you'll have to</i>
<i>carry on without me from here.</i>

151
00:10:04,937 --> 00:10:07,872
<i>It isn't easy to</i>
<i>leave a town like our town...</i>

152
00:10:07,940 --> 00:10:12,477
<i>to tear myself away from you three dear,</i>
<i>dear friends who have meant so much to me.</i>

153
00:10:13,811 --> 00:10:15,904
<i>And so I consider myself</i>
<i>extremely lucky...</i>

154
00:10:15,980 --> 00:10:19,040
<i>to be able to take with me</i>
<i>a sort of memento.</i>

155
00:10:19,116 --> 00:10:23,018
<i>Something to remind me always</i>
<i>of the town that was my home...</i>

156
00:10:23,087 --> 00:10:26,022
<i>and of my three</i>
<i>very dearest friends...</i>

157
00:10:26,090 --> 00:10:28,558
<i>whom I want never to forget.</i>

158
00:10:29,660 --> 00:10:31,685
<i>And I won't.</i>

159
00:10:31,762 --> 00:10:35,926
<i>You see, giris, I've run off with one</i>
<i>of your husbands. Addie.</i>

160
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:39,265
If that's her idea of a joke,
it's in extremely poor taste.

161
00:10:39,337 --> 00:10:41,635
If I ever catch up
with that character, I'll...

162
00:10:45,243 --> 00:10:48,542
<i>Ladies, may I suggest...</i>
<i>The captain seems to think...</i>

163
00:10:48,613 --> 00:10:51,741
Well, he's been rude about it.

164
00:11:48,806 --> 00:11:52,469
Well, looks like Addie has crowned
one of us Queen of the May.

165
00:11:52,543 --> 00:11:54,568
I think it's laughable.

166
00:11:54,645 --> 00:11:56,840
- Okay. Laugh.
- Ha.

167
00:11:56,914 --> 00:12:00,611
Deborah didn't happen to mention
why Brad had to go to the city, did she?

168
00:12:00,685 --> 00:12:04,553
He hasn't missed a Saturday on that golf
course since they got the snow off the greens.

169
00:12:06,591 --> 00:12:09,651
All right, kids.
Get 'em while they're red hot.

170
00:12:14,332 --> 00:12:16,323
It's gonna be a real restful day.

171
00:12:16,400 --> 00:12:18,960
Nothing to think about except
the picnic and the weenie roast...

172
00:12:19,036 --> 00:12:21,027
and coming home.

173
00:12:21,105 --> 00:12:25,474
Oh, that. Kathleen's going
to read us a fairy story.

174
00:12:25,543 --> 00:12:29,172
<i>Fairy story? My favorite kind.</i>
<i>I grew up on them.</i>

175
00:12:29,246 --> 00:12:31,476
Only I wrote my own.

176
00:12:31,549 --> 00:12:34,177
May I start now, Mrs. Bishop?

177
00:12:34,251 --> 00:12:36,481
If you're ready, Kathleen.
Of course.

178
00:12:36,554 --> 00:12:38,988
- "Once..."
- Once.

179
00:12:39,056 --> 00:12:43,993
"Once upon a time,
there lived a very poor girl...

180
00:12:44,061 --> 00:12:46,894
"who was very beautiful.

181
00:12:46,964 --> 00:12:48,226
She was so beautiful..."

182
00:12:49,066 --> 00:12:52,524
<i>Do you remember your first night in town?</i>

183
00:12:52,603 --> 00:12:56,061
<i>You and Brad,</i>
<i>fresh out of the navy.</i>

184
00:12:56,140 --> 00:13:00,042
<i>That was a first Saturday</i>
<i>in May too.</i>

185
00:13:00,111 --> 00:13:02,978
<i>- It it Brad?</i>
<i>- Is it Brad?</i>

186
00:13:03,047 --> 00:13:06,073
<i>- Is it Brad?</i>
<i>- Is it Brad?</i>

187
00:13:06,150 --> 00:13:09,711
<i>- Is it Brad?</i>
<i>- Is it Brad?</i>

188
00:13:17,728 --> 00:13:19,719
Ohhh.

189
00:13:21,465 --> 00:13:25,265
Here now, what's this?
Conduct unbecoming and officer and a lady.

190
00:13:25,336 --> 00:13:27,566
I'm such an unholy mess!

191
00:13:27,638 --> 00:13:29,663
- How?
- This!

192
00:13:29,740 --> 00:13:32,504
- A little too kinky maybe?
- She must've set it with cement.

193
00:13:32,576 --> 00:13:35,977
Mm. Here try this. It'll take
the kink out of a watch spring.

194
00:13:44,955 --> 00:13:47,082
I'm no raving beauty,
heaven knows...

195
00:13:47,158 --> 00:13:50,286
but I did so wanna look
my miserable best tonight.

196
00:13:50,361 --> 00:13:54,058
The very first time we've gone out together
all dressed up like civilians.

197
00:13:57,268 --> 00:13:59,259
And you would be
the one man in the worid...

198
00:13:59,336 --> 00:14:02,169
that looks even better out
of uniform than in.

199
00:14:06,844 --> 00:14:10,109
Got the jumps, kid?

200
00:14:10,181 --> 00:14:13,241
It's been quite a day, that's all.
Quite a change.

201
00:14:13,317 --> 00:14:17,617
Out of the navy, out of uniform.
New home, new town, new friends.

202
00:14:17,688 --> 00:14:21,146
Oh, I told that blasted girl
I wanted to comb it out soft!

203
00:14:21,225 --> 00:14:24,251
It's making me look even more
like a farmhand than I feel.

204
00:14:24,328 --> 00:14:26,990
<i>- Easy does it.</i>
- Meeting your friends for the first time.

205
00:14:27,064 --> 00:14:29,328
You wouldn't want them
to see me like this.

206
00:14:29,400 --> 00:14:33,234
I should hope not.
You be sure to put on a dress.

207
00:14:35,639 --> 00:14:37,698
- Hey! My tie.
- You can tie it again.

208
00:14:40,845 --> 00:14:42,904
There they are.

209
00:14:45,416 --> 00:14:50,786
- Brad, about my dress... you might not like it.
<i>- If you're in it, I'll love it.</i>

210
00:14:50,855 --> 00:14:54,154
It's my only one and years old. Remember
there wasn't time today to get a new one...

211
00:14:54,225 --> 00:14:57,854
and even years ago,
it wasn't exactly the last word.

212
00:14:57,928 --> 00:15:00,021
That was the last word.
Hurry up.

213
00:15:01,432 --> 00:15:03,627
Which ones are they?
I wanna have it right.

214
00:15:03,701 --> 00:15:06,101
Rita and George Phipps.
We all grew up together.

215
00:15:06,170 --> 00:15:08,161
He teaches at the high school,
they have twins...

216
00:15:08,239 --> 00:15:10,264
and she just got a job
writing for the radio.

217
00:15:10,341 --> 00:15:13,640
Did you like her very much...
when you grew up together, I mean.

218
00:15:13,711 --> 00:15:16,942
Rita and George were engaged
at the age of five by swapping beetles.

219
00:15:17,014 --> 00:15:19,448
- She was never my type.
- What is your type?

220
00:15:19,517 --> 00:15:21,712
Fat, squat, little brunettes
with mustaches.

221
00:15:21,786 --> 00:15:24,721
Get going... and take another whack
at that hair.

222
00:15:45,142 --> 00:15:48,168
The original will be down
in person directly.

223
00:15:48,245 --> 00:15:50,338
- Brad! Hi, darling.
- Hello, Rita.

224
00:15:50,414 --> 00:15:52,507
- George.
- Hello, Brad. You look fine.

225
00:15:52,583 --> 00:15:54,642
- I feel fine.
- Good to see you.

226
00:15:54,718 --> 00:15:57,710
What's this I hear about twins?
You look like a fugitive from a junior prom.

227
00:15:57,788 --> 00:15:59,813
Oh, not next to that, I don't.

228
00:15:59,890 --> 00:16:03,155
- Brad, she's adorable.
- My personal share of navy surplus.

229
00:16:03,227 --> 00:16:05,855
She certainly doesn't look
as if she grew up on a farm.

230
00:16:05,930 --> 00:16:09,195
Darling, I'm sure she took the hay out of
her mouth while she was being photographed.

231
00:16:09,266 --> 00:16:11,257
Don't be funny, dear.

232
00:16:11,335 --> 00:16:14,930
What I meant was that
from Brad's letter, I imagined all sorts of...

233
00:16:15,005 --> 00:16:19,066
Well, anyway, just where on Fifth Avenue
was this farm she came from?

234
00:16:19,143 --> 00:16:21,543
It's like music to hear
you two pick at each other.

235
00:16:21,612 --> 00:16:23,739
Oh, we've declared an armistice for tonight...

236
00:16:23,814 --> 00:16:25,839
out of respect
for your battle fatigue.

237
00:16:25,916 --> 00:16:29,215
Fine. Well, here it is again.
The first Saturday night in May.

238
00:16:29,286 --> 00:16:32,016
And here we are.
You two, Porter and Lora Mae.

239
00:16:32,089 --> 00:16:34,523
We'll all be together again,
just the way it used to be.

240
00:16:34,592 --> 00:16:37,891
Uh, well, not exactly as it used to be.

241
00:16:37,962 --> 00:16:41,295
It seems there's been a change
in one of the characters.

242
00:16:41,365 --> 00:16:45,267
Yeah. Not <i>exactly</i>
the same old six.

243
00:16:45,336 --> 00:16:47,429
Tell me, how is Addie?

244
00:16:52,877 --> 00:16:56,313
Rita and George, Deborah.
Debby, Rita and George Phipps.

245
00:16:56,380 --> 00:16:58,473
They were with me the day
I swallowed my first worm...

246
00:16:58,549 --> 00:17:00,642
and I hope will be there
when I swallow my last.

247
00:17:00,718 --> 00:17:02,743
That's the most disgusting
introduction I ever heard.

248
00:17:02,820 --> 00:17:04,811
- Hello, Deborah. Welcome.
- Thank you.

249
00:17:04,889 --> 00:17:07,449
- How do you do, Deborah?
- How do you do?

250
00:17:07,524 --> 00:17:10,493
Well, the occasiףn calls for a drink...
a quick one, because we're late.

251
00:17:10,561 --> 00:17:13,121
- Uh, we've been admiring your photograph.
- Yes.

252
00:17:13,197 --> 00:17:16,963
It's a very flattering one.
Maybe it's the uniform.

253
00:17:17,034 --> 00:17:20,629
For some reason or other, I always seem
to be wearing a full beard in photographs.

254
00:17:20,704 --> 00:17:23,832
- You know, even in snapshots as a child, l...
- Give me a hand, George.

255
00:17:23,908 --> 00:17:26,138
Uh, excuse me.

256
00:17:29,747 --> 00:17:31,840
I don't think it's particularly flattering.

257
00:17:31,916 --> 00:17:34,316
Nice of you to say so, but it is.

258
00:17:34,385 --> 00:17:38,014
Well, here's to Deb. And here's to us
and many happy returns of this day.

259
00:17:38,088 --> 00:17:40,249
- I'll drink to that.
- Amen.

260
00:17:42,826 --> 00:17:45,522
Ah. Now, if I can remember
my way to the club...

261
00:17:45,596 --> 00:17:48,087
<i>Oh, before we go, I have to call</i>
<i>the house and see if the sitter's showed up.</i>

262
00:17:48,165 --> 00:17:51,464
- It's Sadie's night out.
- Well, why not call from upstairs?

263
00:17:51,535 --> 00:17:53,867
I have to get my bag anyway.

264
00:17:53,938 --> 00:17:56,031
Good idea.

265
00:17:58,342 --> 00:18:01,175
Now, don't make a tribal ceremony
out of it, giris. We're late now.

266
00:18:01,245 --> 00:18:03,270
- Huh huh.
- George and I will get the car and wait outside.

267
00:18:03,347 --> 00:18:05,975
- Mm-hmm.
- Remember, we'll be waiting outside.

268
00:18:06,050 --> 00:18:08,541
- Uh-huh.
- Ready, George?

269
00:18:08,619 --> 00:18:11,986
Mm? Oh.

270
00:18:12,056 --> 00:18:15,321
- Oh, they finally put a traffic light at that dip
on Orchard Avenue.
- Yeah?

271
00:18:15,392 --> 00:18:17,622
The Mayor cracked
his upper plate there last Christmas.

272
00:18:19,863 --> 00:18:23,299
All the doors and windows are locked.
Don't worry about them.

273
00:18:23,367 --> 00:18:25,426
What?

274
00:18:27,271 --> 00:18:30,172
Certainly not. They're old enough
to do that by themselves.

275
00:18:30,240 --> 00:18:32,936
We'll be at the country club.
Fine. Good night.

276
00:18:34,278 --> 00:18:36,371
Well...

277
00:18:37,414 --> 00:18:39,678
- Something wrong?
- No.

278
00:18:39,750 --> 00:18:42,810
The bugle sounds.

279
00:18:42,886 --> 00:18:46,754
I think I've got a sick headache
and can't go.

280
00:18:46,824 --> 00:18:48,849
Then there is something wrong.

281
00:18:48,926 --> 00:18:50,985
Me. I'm wrong.

282
00:18:52,930 --> 00:18:55,592
What do you mean? How?

283
00:18:55,666 --> 00:18:58,931
Every which way.
For Brad. For his friends.

284
00:18:59,003 --> 00:19:01,233
You, your husband,
the others I haven't met yet.

285
00:19:01,305 --> 00:19:04,172
The country club.
The town.

286
00:19:04,241 --> 00:19:07,506
I'm scared.
I'm so scared, I'm sick.

287
00:19:15,285 --> 00:19:18,948
Isn't there a nice baseball game or something
you children can listen to on the radio?

288
00:19:19,023 --> 00:19:21,787
<i>- What's going on up there?</i>
- I'm, uh...

289
00:19:21,859 --> 00:19:23,952
I'm having a little slip trouble.

290
00:19:24,028 --> 00:19:26,121
<i>- Oh. Hurry it up!</i>
- Uh-huh.

291
00:19:33,437 --> 00:19:36,031
Looks like somebody
had a lot of martinis.

292
00:19:37,107 --> 00:19:39,166
I did.

293
00:19:41,145 --> 00:19:43,136
What are you so scared of?

294
00:19:43,213 --> 00:19:45,238
It's worst than my first night
in the WAVES.

295
00:19:45,315 --> 00:19:48,284
And I'd never been away from home
before up until then.

296
00:19:48,352 --> 00:19:50,377
But we were all in the same spot.

297
00:19:50,454 --> 00:19:52,752
Everything was happening
to all of us for the first time.

298
00:19:52,823 --> 00:19:56,486
Mm. And here you're
the only new girl, is that it?

299
00:19:58,028 --> 00:20:01,293
Look. You're Brad's wife
and our friend.

300
00:20:01,365 --> 00:20:03,595
We want you here
and we've waited for you.

301
00:20:03,667 --> 00:20:08,263
Now, why shouldn't that make you feel
safe and secure instead of being scared?

302
00:20:08,338 --> 00:20:11,933
You can't be safe and secure
by just telling yourself to feel it.

303
00:20:12,009 --> 00:20:15,240
Unless, maybe, you've got twins
and a job of your own...

304
00:20:15,312 --> 00:20:17,872
and grown up with your husband
and friends.

305
00:20:19,650 --> 00:20:22,118
Oh, I'm sorry.
I didn't mean that.

306
00:20:22,186 --> 00:20:24,177
Blame it on the martinis.

307
00:20:24,254 --> 00:20:26,745
You know, counting ice water...

308
00:20:26,824 --> 00:20:28,892
we could squeeze two more
out of this shaker.

309
00:20:29,025 --> 00:20:32,586
Oh, no. No.

310
00:20:32,662 --> 00:20:36,723
I've had more tonight than all the rest
of my life put together.

311
00:20:38,501 --> 00:20:40,526
What was it like at home?

312
00:20:40,603 --> 00:20:43,697
<i>Or should I mind my own business?</i>

313
00:20:45,875 --> 00:20:48,639
Ever read in the picture magazines
about Farmer So-and-so...

314
00:20:48,711 --> 00:20:51,145
and his model farm,
kitchen and life?

315
00:20:51,214 --> 00:20:53,842
Well, it wasn't us
or anybody we knew.

316
00:20:53,917 --> 00:20:55,942
Papa'd just get through
paying for the thresher...

317
00:20:56,019 --> 00:20:58,453
in time to start paying
on the new separator.

318
00:20:58,521 --> 00:21:02,321
Till I was 13, a bus took me three miles
that way to grammar school.

319
00:21:02,392 --> 00:21:05,953
Till I was 17, another bus took me
11 miles that way to high school.

320
00:21:06,029 --> 00:21:08,122
And after that, I stayed home.

321
00:21:08,197 --> 00:21:10,722
Till one day I took a bus
58 miles that way...

322
00:21:10,800 --> 00:21:12,927
to join the navy
and see the worid.

323
00:21:15,038 --> 00:21:17,836
And meet Brad "Bripaship."

324
00:21:17,907 --> 00:21:20,398
Fall in love
and marry Brad "Bripaship."

325
00:21:23,746 --> 00:21:26,715
Why not?

326
00:21:26,783 --> 00:21:32,016
"Why not?" I said to myself. I was quite a girl
in the navy. Head of my class. Hooray for me.

327
00:21:32,088 --> 00:21:34,716
And pretty cute in that uniform.

328
00:21:34,791 --> 00:21:37,726
That uniform...
it's the great "leveleller."

329
00:21:39,829 --> 00:21:42,764
<i>You couldn't tell me</i>
<i>from Vassar or Smith or Long Island.</i>

330
00:21:42,832 --> 00:21:47,428
That was the girl in the picture on the piano.
That isn't me. This is me.

331
00:21:50,006 --> 00:21:52,236
What do you people talk about?

332
00:21:52,308 --> 00:21:56,210
Years of growing up together. Thousands
of first names and private memories.

333
00:21:56,279 --> 00:21:59,942
How do I fit in? Running a house,
making friends, filling the day.

334
00:22:00,016 --> 00:22:02,246
Mrs. Bradbury Bishop.
"What's she like?"

335
00:22:02,318 --> 00:22:04,343
"Fun to be with, smart as a whip,
pretty too.

336
00:22:04,420 --> 00:22:07,048
No wonder Brad Bishop married her,
the lucky stiff."

337
00:22:07,123 --> 00:22:09,557
Rita, look at me.
Look at my mail-order dress...

338
00:22:09,625 --> 00:22:11,616
that's four years old
and awful even then.

339
00:22:11,694 --> 00:22:13,787
What am I gonna do?

340
00:22:17,333 --> 00:22:19,767
As if that really mattered.

341
00:22:19,836 --> 00:22:22,327
You must think we're
an awful bunch of snobs.

342
00:22:24,207 --> 00:22:27,904
Aren't you underestimating us
a little bit and Brad even more?

343
00:22:27,977 --> 00:22:30,810
You know, it's just possible
he knew what he wanted and you had it.

344
00:22:30,880 --> 00:22:32,905
And if you had it, you still got it.

345
00:22:35,184 --> 00:22:37,709
I can't hear you. Sit up.

346
00:22:37,787 --> 00:22:40,813
I said, "Thank you
for the kind words."

347
00:22:40,890 --> 00:22:44,587
You're welcome.
Now, about the dress.

348
00:22:44,660 --> 00:22:47,288
- Haven't you anything else?
- Only uniforms.

349
00:22:47,363 --> 00:22:49,456
Oh. Well, stand up.

350
00:22:51,968 --> 00:22:55,233
- The flowers must go.
- Flowers must go.

351
00:22:55,304 --> 00:22:57,295
Have you any scissors?

352
00:23:02,178 --> 00:23:05,011
- Scissors?
- Oh.

353
00:23:05,081 --> 00:23:07,914
I'll get the ones on the sleeves.
You tackle the big one in the middle.

354
00:23:10,520 --> 00:23:12,579
- Careful now.
- Careful now.

355
00:23:16,893 --> 00:23:18,986
Now look what I did!

356
00:23:19,062 --> 00:23:21,690
Oh. You don't want
a bare midriff, do you?

357
00:23:21,764 --> 00:23:24,426
Tsk. Well, back goes the flower.

358
00:23:24,500 --> 00:23:26,764
Sit down. Have you
got any safety pins?

359
00:23:26,836 --> 00:23:28,895
- Bottom drawer.
- Oh.

360
00:23:58,468 --> 00:24:01,631
- More wine?
- Thank you. No.

361
00:24:05,575 --> 00:24:07,805
Not much at dancing.
It makes me nervous.

362
00:24:07,877 --> 00:24:10,072
<i>- Does it?</i>
- Whatever I do, I wanna do well.

363
00:24:10,146 --> 00:24:12,478
Can't do a thing well,
leave it alone, I always say.

364
00:24:14,150 --> 00:24:17,551
I think I will have
a little more wine, thank you.

365
00:24:24,727 --> 00:24:27,389
Thank you very much.

366
00:24:27,463 --> 00:24:31,160
Especially the rumba. Gotta have Spanish blood
or something, like my wife.

367
00:24:31,234 --> 00:24:33,668
Comes from an old Spanish family
named Finney.

368
00:24:33,736 --> 00:24:35,727
In many South American countries...

369
00:24:35,805 --> 00:24:38,433
there are many very distinguished families
with Irish names.

370
00:24:51,454 --> 00:24:55,413
Lora Mae looks good with Brad.
Looks like class. But it's him, not her.

371
00:24:55,491 --> 00:24:58,119
If she was dancin' with a tramp,
she'd look like a tramp.

372
00:24:58,194 --> 00:25:00,219
Got no class of her own.

373
00:25:00,296 --> 00:25:02,287
I like class.

374
00:25:02,365 --> 00:25:04,390
- You like class?
- Oh, very much.

375
00:25:04,467 --> 00:25:07,630
You hit the jackpot.
Brad Bishop... class plus money.

376
00:25:07,703 --> 00:25:09,864
Yes, sir. The jackpot and you hit it.

377
00:25:09,939 --> 00:25:13,534
Count 'em on the fingers of one hand
in this town... throw away some fingers even.

378
00:25:13,609 --> 00:25:16,806
There's... There's Brad and who else?

379
00:25:16,879 --> 00:25:18,904
Yeah. There's Addie.

380
00:25:18,981 --> 00:25:20,972
Addie? Addie who?

381
00:25:21,050 --> 00:25:23,712
Ross. Addie Ross.

382
00:25:23,786 --> 00:25:28,120
- Funny. People always figured
Brad and Addie would...
- Brad and Addie what?

383
00:25:28,191 --> 00:25:32,457
The samba can be danced properly
only on the side of a hill on ice.

384
00:25:32,528 --> 00:25:34,962
Alibi. He was afraid
of getting wrinkles in his new suit.

385
00:25:35,031 --> 00:25:37,056
Oh, my first new party dress
in years...

386
00:25:37,133 --> 00:25:39,431
thanks to my dear wife
and her millions of listeners...

387
00:25:39,502 --> 00:25:41,493
including the armed forces overseas.

388
00:25:41,571 --> 00:25:44,972
Shall we drink to them all...
one by one?

389
00:25:45,041 --> 00:25:49,569
- How about some coffee?
- George. I think your tuxedo has got class, George.

390
00:25:49,645 --> 00:25:53,103
- We thank you.
<i>- Funny thing for a wife</i>
<i>to give her husband a tuxedo.</i>

391
00:25:53,182 --> 00:25:56,481
- An even funnier thing
for a husband to give his wife.

392
00:25:56,552 --> 00:25:58,747
Come on, Deborah.
While the coffee's nice and hot.

393
00:25:58,821 --> 00:26:02,450
- You're so funny, George.
- I still don't think a woman
oughta buy clothes for a man.

394
00:26:02,525 --> 00:26:04,516
- It's about time they start.
- Contrary to nature.

395
00:26:04,594 --> 00:26:06,619
Oh, tell us about nature, Porter.

396
00:26:06,696 --> 00:26:09,028
It's a man's worid, yeah.

397
00:26:09,098 --> 00:26:11,760
See something you want,
go after it and get it. That's nature.

398
00:26:11,834 --> 00:26:13,825
It's why we're made strong
and women weak.

399
00:26:13,903 --> 00:26:16,963
Strong conqueror provides for the weak.
That's what a man's for.

400
00:26:17,039 --> 00:26:19,371
Teach our kids more of that,
there'll be more men.

401
00:26:19,442 --> 00:26:22,138
And more war.
Leave my kids out.

402
00:26:22,211 --> 00:26:24,441
But those standards don't apply to me, Porter...

403
00:26:24,513 --> 00:26:27,949
because in this man's worid,
I'm not a man.

404
00:26:28,017 --> 00:26:30,144
- I'm a schoolteacher.
- The dance is over.

405
00:26:30,219 --> 00:26:32,210
<i>I knew we'd get around to that.</i>

406
00:26:32,288 --> 00:26:34,848
All right.
Schoolteachers oughta get paid more.

407
00:26:34,924 --> 00:26:36,949
<i>And what happens if they're not?</i>

408
00:26:37,026 --> 00:26:40,462
How does a schoolteacher
provide for the weak?

409
00:26:40,529 --> 00:26:43,327
How does he pay the rent
with the plays and poems of Shakespeare?

410
00:26:43,399 --> 00:26:45,867
Have you been shooting off
your big mouth again?

411
00:26:45,935 --> 00:26:48,335
You just shut up till
it's time to dance again.

412
00:26:48,404 --> 00:26:50,395
<i>Let me tell you about nature</i>
<i>making men strong.</i>

413
00:26:50,473 --> 00:26:53,567
Einstein couldn't kick a football
across this dance floor...

414
00:26:53,643 --> 00:26:55,668
but he changed
the shape of the universe.

415
00:26:55,745 --> 00:26:59,010
Now, take it easy, everybody.
This is getting a little out of hand.

416
00:26:59,081 --> 00:27:02,517
You never know what he'll come up with
when he starts knocking on that brandy bottle.

417
00:27:02,585 --> 00:27:04,576
You shut up.
You just shut up.

418
00:27:04,654 --> 00:27:07,817
Isn't it fun, Deborah?
We're all pals. You know, buddies.

419
00:27:07,890 --> 00:27:09,983
Just one big happy family.

420
00:27:12,128 --> 00:27:15,996
<i>- Why, Brad!</i>
- Not me, but it's a good idea.

421
00:27:16,065 --> 00:27:18,226
With the compliments
of Mrs. Addie Ross.

422
00:27:18,301 --> 00:27:20,769
Oh, Porter, you were saying
something about her and Brad.

423
00:27:20,836 --> 00:27:22,827
Addie.

424
00:27:25,574 --> 00:27:30,068
- John, where is Mrs. Ross?
- I don't believe she's arrived yet, Mr. Bishop.

425
00:27:30,146 --> 00:27:34,515
That's Addie for you.
Always the right thing at the right time.

426
00:27:34,583 --> 00:27:37,245
<i>- Thoughtful and generous.</i>
- Generous to a fault.

427
00:27:37,320 --> 00:27:39,550
To a fault. That's Addie.

428
00:27:39,622 --> 00:27:42,591
Who is Mr. Ross?

429
00:27:42,658 --> 00:27:45,786
Mr. Ross took a powder
about five years ago.

430
00:27:45,861 --> 00:27:48,227
No such thing.
She gave him the heave-ho.

431
00:27:48,297 --> 00:27:51,698
He went out for a paper one night
and never came back.

432
00:27:51,767 --> 00:27:54,736
Porter says Addie Ross
has got class.

433
00:27:54,804 --> 00:27:58,240
And he knows class
like I know navigation.

434
00:27:58,307 --> 00:28:01,765
You stick to your guns, Porter.
It shows a healthy instinct.

435
00:28:01,844 --> 00:28:05,075
You may call it "class,"
but what Addie has is taste.

436
