782
00:50:28,523 --> 00:50:32,755
My, that was fun. Two whole hours.

783
00:50:32,827 --> 00:50:35,625
<i>Linda</i> ran over almost a minute.

784
00:50:35,697 --> 00:50:38,131
- The third time in a month.
- Three minutes gone...

785
00:50:38,199 --> 00:50:41,327
one full commercial,
gone for good.

786
00:50:41,402 --> 00:50:44,997
Well, some more coffee anybody?

787
00:50:45,073 --> 00:50:47,098
- George?
- Hmm?

788
00:50:47,175 --> 00:50:50,633
- Oh, uh, some more coffee, anybody?
- I just asked everybody, dear.

789
00:50:50,712 --> 00:50:53,772
- Well, time to go home.
- Already?

790
00:50:53,848 --> 00:50:55,839
Seems as if you just got here.

791
00:50:55,917 --> 00:50:59,409
- Come on, Giant. Back to the bean stalk.
<i>- Get your coat. I'm ready.</i>

792
00:50:59,487 --> 00:51:02,650
Been such a lovely evening, my dear.
Pleasant company.

793
00:51:02,724 --> 00:51:05,454
- The duck was fine.
- Of course, eating out here
off your laps, gypsy fashion...

794
00:51:05,526 --> 00:51:08,154
- The time just flew by.
<i>- Tempo fugit.</i>

795
00:51:08,229 --> 00:51:10,322
- Right, Professor?
- Almost.

796
00:51:10,398 --> 00:51:14,562
- And our little hostess has her work to do.
- Oh, it's not so much.

797
00:51:20,375 --> 00:51:23,970
<i>Perhaps we can drive out and have lunch</i>
<i>with you one day soon, Mr. Hollingsway.</i>

798
00:51:24,045 --> 00:51:25,945
Maybe at one of the other stores.

799
00:51:26,014 --> 00:51:29,711
We'll make our appointment
well in advance and at your convenience.

800
00:51:29,784 --> 00:51:32,844
You're gonna be a giant.
Relax and enjoy it.

801
00:51:32,921 --> 00:51:36,322
I hope you listened
conscientiously, my dear.

802
00:51:36,391 --> 00:51:40,623
Particularly to <i>Linda Gray.</i>
You can learn a great deal about writing.

803
00:51:40,695 --> 00:51:44,290
- Yes, they are well-written, aren't they?
- Why, they're perfection.

804
00:51:47,435 --> 00:51:49,460
Didn't you think so, Mr. Phipps?

805
00:51:49,537 --> 00:51:52,062
Oh, I beg your pardon.
I wasn't listening.

806
00:51:52,140 --> 00:51:54,165
We'll see how much
of an expert you are.

807
00:51:54,242 --> 00:51:56,233
Which of the programs
did you think was the best?

808
00:51:56,311 --> 00:51:59,178
They all sounded
pretty much alike to me.

809
00:51:59,247 --> 00:52:01,977
Uh, I thought you were
a student of good writing.

810
00:52:02,050 --> 00:52:04,041
Oh, he is.
He's given courses in the university.

811
00:52:04,118 --> 00:52:08,077
- Then which was the best?
- I wish you wouldn't ask me that.

812
00:52:08,156 --> 00:52:11,557
<i>- Why not?</i>
- Because it's a question I don't want to answer.

813
00:52:11,626 --> 00:52:15,722
Oh, go ahead, dear. I'm sure your opinion
is a very valuable one.

814
00:52:15,797 --> 00:52:19,358
- Well, if you're sure you want me to.
- Not if you feel you shouldn't.

815
00:52:19,434 --> 00:52:21,925
Stating it as kindly as I can,
Mrs. Manleigh...

816
00:52:22,003 --> 00:52:25,234
none of that bilge has the remotest connection
with good writing.

817
00:52:25,306 --> 00:52:28,332
Do you realize that <i>Linda Gray</i>
has been written for eight years...

818
00:52:28,409 --> 00:52:30,502
no summer layoff,
by Myrtle Tippet?

819
00:52:30,578 --> 00:52:33,672
- Who?
- You can't be much of an authority, Mr. Phipps...

820
00:52:33,748 --> 00:52:35,739
if you don't know Myrtle Tippet.

821
00:52:35,817 --> 00:52:39,082
<i>Linda Gray</i> has made her an immortal,
and she's only 32.

822
00:52:39,153 --> 00:52:42,919
Well, Keats, Shelley and Marlowe beat her
by a couple of years anyway.

823
00:52:42,991 --> 00:52:45,016
They were immortal
before they were 30.

824
00:52:45,093 --> 00:52:48,062
- Classroom stuff.
- Radio writing is the literature of today.

825
00:52:48,129 --> 00:52:51,690
- The literature of the masses!
- Then heaven help the masses.

826
00:52:51,766 --> 00:52:53,859
Well, it just serves
a different purpose, that's all.

827
00:52:53,935 --> 00:52:56,904
The purpose of radio writing,
as far as I can see...

828
00:52:56,971 --> 00:52:59,599
is to prove to the masses
that a deodorant can bring happiness...

829
00:52:59,674 --> 00:53:02,871
a mouthwash guarantee success
and a laxative attract romance.

830
00:53:02,944 --> 00:53:06,107
- Well!
<i>- Take it easy, George.</i>

831
00:53:06,180 --> 00:53:08,740
Let him alone.
He'll run longer than <i>Linda Gray.</i>

832
00:53:08,816 --> 00:53:11,410
"Don't think," says the radio,
"and we'll pay you for it.

833
00:53:11,486 --> 00:53:13,477
"Can't spell 'cat'?
Too bad.

834
00:53:13,554 --> 00:53:15,579
"But a yacht and a million dollars
to the gentleman...

835
00:53:15,656 --> 00:53:17,647
for being in our audience tonight."

836
00:53:17,725 --> 00:53:20,159
"Worry," says the radio.
"Will your best friends not tell you?

837
00:53:20,228 --> 00:53:22,890
"Will you lose your teeth?
Will your cigarettes give you cancer?

838
00:53:22,964 --> 00:53:25,057
"Will your body function
after you're 35?

839
00:53:25,133 --> 00:53:28,500
"If you don't use our product,
you lose your husband, your job and die!

840
00:53:28,569 --> 00:53:31,231
Use our product and we'll make you rich,
we'll make you famous!"

841
00:53:31,305 --> 00:53:33,296
That's just about enough, George.

842
00:53:33,374 --> 00:53:36,104
Don't let it upset you, my dear.
Don't you feel badly.

843
00:53:36,177 --> 00:53:39,806
"Bad," not "badly"!
You feel badly this way!

844
00:53:39,881 --> 00:53:44,682
I have more confidence than ever
in your understanding of domestic problems.

845
00:53:44,752 --> 00:53:49,621
- Look. I got my coat on and I catch cold easy.
- "Easily," not "easy."

846
00:53:49,690 --> 00:53:52,318
We're leaving now, Mr. Hollingsway.

847
00:53:52,393 --> 00:53:54,418
- Good night again, my dear.
- Good night.

848
00:53:54,495 --> 00:53:56,861
Of course you understand
that under the circumstances...

849
00:53:56,931 --> 00:53:59,126
your little project
is quite, quite impossible.

850
00:53:59,200 --> 00:54:01,191
- Uh, of course.
- Good night, Mr. Phipps.

851
00:54:01,269 --> 00:54:02,759
Good night.

852
00:54:06,240 --> 00:54:08,265
- Good night, Rita. So long, George.
- Good night.

853
00:54:08,342 --> 00:54:10,173
- Good night, kids.
- Good night, Lora Mae.

854
00:54:12,246 --> 00:54:16,114
What little project of yours turned out
to be quite, quite impossible?

855
00:54:22,190 --> 00:54:25,557
I'll take care of tidying up.
You better start your revisions.

856
00:54:25,626 --> 00:54:27,719
It's all right.

857
00:54:29,397 --> 00:54:32,366
I'm sorry about this.

858
00:54:32,433 --> 00:54:34,424
I know how much it means to you.

859
00:54:35,736 --> 00:54:38,398
Well, it couldn't be helped,
I guess.

860
00:54:38,473 --> 00:54:41,840
Oh, George, it would have been so simple
to say something noncommittal.

861
00:54:41,909 --> 00:54:45,345
Not for three hours it isn't.
I held back all night.

862
00:54:45,413 --> 00:54:49,008
Anyway, she doesn't blame you for it.
Didn't she tell you not to feel badly?

863
00:54:49,083 --> 00:54:53,520
- I wasn't thinking of myself.
- What can she do to me?
Report me as being un-American?

864
00:54:53,588 --> 00:54:55,488
Radio's like a religion
to those people.

865
00:54:55,556 --> 00:54:57,581
When you attack it,
you attack their faith.

866
00:54:57,658 --> 00:54:59,853
Once they've seen you against it,
they're off of you for life.

867
00:54:59,927 --> 00:55:02,657
- There's no making it up.
- Why should I want to make it up?

868
00:55:04,265 --> 00:55:07,166
Why should I?

869
00:55:07,235 --> 00:55:09,635
Oh, nothing.

870
00:55:21,182 --> 00:55:23,412
You know, this is getting to be
like a good mystery story...

871
00:55:23,484 --> 00:55:26,749
where you think you got the murderer
picked out and it turns out to be somebody else.

872
00:55:26,821 --> 00:55:29,585
For just a minute,
I had your little project tied up with Porter.

873
00:55:29,657 --> 00:55:31,955
But now the clues
seem to point to me.

874
00:55:32,026 --> 00:55:34,085
In some weird, unimaginable way...

875
00:55:34,162 --> 00:55:36,630
I was to prove irresistible
to Mrs. Manleigh tonight.

876
00:55:36,697 --> 00:55:38,790
I was to impress her
and win her favor.

877
00:55:38,866 --> 00:55:41,232
Isn't that so?

878
00:55:41,302 --> 00:55:44,100
But why?
To what purpose?

879
00:55:44,172 --> 00:55:46,367
Well, if you must know,
there are editors leaving...

880
00:55:46,440 --> 00:55:48,431
and I thought you'd be
perfect for the job.

881
00:55:48,509 --> 00:55:50,602
$175 a week to start.

882
00:55:57,185 --> 00:55:59,813
Come here.

883
00:55:59,887 --> 00:56:01,980
Sit down for a minute.

884
00:56:04,325 --> 00:56:08,659
Look, Reet, let's put aside my nausea
at the idea of working for the Manleighs.

885
00:56:08,729 --> 00:56:11,994
Let's put aside my personal likes and dislikes.
They're not important.

886
00:56:12,066 --> 00:56:14,933
I'm willing to admit
that to a majority of my fellow citizens...

887
00:56:15,002 --> 00:56:18,062
I'm a slightly comic figure...
an educated man.

888
00:56:18,139 --> 00:56:20,972
Nobody's asking you not to be.
Think of the good you could do.

889
00:56:21,042 --> 00:56:23,272
- Maybe raise the standard.
- Of commercial radio?

890
00:56:23,344 --> 00:56:26,780
What's the phrase...
"Wait for your laugh"?

891
00:56:26,847 --> 00:56:30,783
I'm a schoolteacher.
That's even worse than being an intellectual.

892
00:56:30,851 --> 00:56:32,842
Schoolteachers are not only comic...

893
00:56:32,920 --> 00:56:35,753
they're often cold and hungry
in this richest land on Earth.

894
00:56:35,823 --> 00:56:39,315
And thousands are quitting every year
to take jobs that pay them a decent living.

895
00:56:39,393 --> 00:56:41,418
- That is unhappily true.
- Then why not you?

896
00:56:41,495 --> 00:56:44,487
Because I can't think of myself
doing anything else.

897
00:56:46,667 --> 00:56:49,329
What would happen,
do ya think, if we all quit?

898
00:56:49,403 --> 00:56:52,861
Who'll teach the kids?
Who'd open their minds and hearts...

899
00:56:52,940 --> 00:56:56,034
to the real glories of the human spirit
past and present.

900
00:56:56,110 --> 00:56:58,135
Who'd help them along to the future?

901
00:56:58,212 --> 00:57:00,806
Radio sponsors?
Comic strips?

902
00:57:00,881 --> 00:57:02,872
At that, I've been
luckier than most.

903
00:57:02,950 --> 00:57:06,215
Even without what you earn,
I've managed to keep our heads above water.

904
00:57:06,287 --> 00:57:09,518
It's quite a strain over a period of time
with the water lapping at your chin.

905
00:57:09,590 --> 00:57:11,615
That's where
you've been a great help.

906
00:57:11,692 --> 00:57:14,286
You've made it a lot easier
for both of us.

907
00:57:14,362 --> 00:57:17,854
I'll admit is has upset
my male ego from time to time.

908
00:57:17,932 --> 00:57:21,800
And your overdeveloped
sense of taste and discrimination...

909
00:57:21,869 --> 00:57:24,861
which is apparently equaled
only by that of Addie Ross.

910
00:57:24,939 --> 00:57:27,032
Let's try to keep Addie
out of this one.

911
00:57:27,108 --> 00:57:30,278
I am fed up with taste
and discrimination.

912
00:57:32,113 --> 00:57:35,640
- You're not making sense.
- I'm fed up with your nobility
and wisdom and superiority...

913
00:57:35,716 --> 00:57:38,947
- and your contempt for me
in everything I try to do.
- You're talking nonsense.

914
00:57:39,020 --> 00:57:42,922
- Everything I say is nonsense.
- It's all this work. You're overtired.
You do too much.

915
00:57:42,990 --> 00:57:45,652
What do you suggest I stop doing,
this moronic radio trash...

916
00:57:45,726 --> 00:57:47,819
- with which I pay most of your bills?
- Now calm down.

917
00:57:47,895 --> 00:57:49,988
And what do I go back to,
washing, scrubbing, ironing...

918
00:57:50,064 --> 00:57:52,123
and a life of taste
and discrimination?

919
00:57:52,199 --> 00:57:54,326
I'm fed up with Addie Ross!

920
00:57:56,370 --> 00:58:00,204
- What's it all about, really?
- "If music be the food of love... play on."

921
00:58:00,274 --> 00:58:04,142
"Give me excess of it, that, surfeiting,
the appetite may sicken, and so die.

922
00:58:04,211 --> 00:58:07,146
From <i>Twelfth Night,</i> by Mr. Shakespeare,
which Addie and I played in high school.

923
00:58:07,214 --> 00:58:09,341
I thought it was a very clever note.

924
00:58:09,417 --> 00:58:11,510
And there was more to it
than a childhood memory.

925
00:58:11,585 --> 00:58:13,678
Yes, there was,
but we won't go into that.

926
00:58:13,754 --> 00:58:16,382
We're going to get a few things
straightened out once and for all. Sit down.

927
00:58:16,457 --> 00:58:18,755
- Yes, professor.
- Sit down!

928
00:58:18,826 --> 00:58:23,525
Seven years ago I made the most perfect
marriage ever devised by man, heaven or radio.

929
00:58:23,597 --> 00:58:26,065
My wife was an independent,
understanding woman.

930
00:58:26,133 --> 00:58:29,660
We thought the same thing
about everything, from baseball to Brahms.

931
00:58:29,737 --> 00:58:32,763
In those seven years, I was never
contemptuous of you. I was proud.

932
00:58:32,840 --> 00:58:36,469
But when that drooling pap
began to change you...

933
00:58:36,544 --> 00:58:38,637
when your independence
turned to fear...

934
00:58:38,713 --> 00:58:42,740
when I watched you snivel and grovel around
those two walking commercials...

935
00:58:42,817 --> 00:58:45,581
<i>I didn't like it,</i>
<i>and I don't like it.</i>

936
00:58:45,653 --> 00:58:47,883
I don't want to be
married to Linda Gray...

937
00:58:47,955 --> 00:58:50,219
Brenda Brown
or even Myrtle Tippet.

938
00:58:50,291 --> 00:58:52,521
I want my own wife back.

939
00:59:02,403 --> 00:59:07,636
<i>Why didn't George go fishing?</i>

940
00:59:12,646 --> 00:59:16,047
<i>Why the blue suit?</i>

941
00:59:39,373 --> 00:59:41,432
Lora Mae?

942
00:59:45,780 --> 00:59:48,442
Lora Mae, are you ready?

943
00:59:48,516 --> 00:59:50,848
Oh.

944
00:59:50,918 --> 00:59:54,376
My, all that running,
hiking and baseball...

945
00:59:54,455 --> 00:59:56,548
your feet must be ready
to drop off.

946
00:59:56,624 --> 00:59:59,115
I've covered more ground in Porter's store
from the notion's counter...

947
00:59:59,193 --> 01:00:02,492
- just back and forth to the water cooler.
- How's it feel, Lora Mae?

948
01:00:02,563 --> 01:00:07,933
Porter spreading out on a national scale,
gonna be a big merchant prince.

949
01:00:08,002 --> 01:00:13,907
- How's it supposed to feel?
- No more small towns for Porter.
He'll be after the big cities.

950
01:00:13,974 --> 01:00:18,411
He'll be after... what is it
he always calls it... class?

951
01:00:18,479 --> 01:00:23,314
Look, why don't I save you a lot of trouble
and tell you what you want to know...

952
01:00:23,384 --> 01:00:26,410
and you can tell Debby and that'll
keep you busy until I'm dressed.

953
01:00:26,487 --> 01:00:30,150
I don't know whether Porter ran off
with Addie, but get this... I don't care.

954
01:00:30,224 --> 01:00:33,250
I've got everything I want.

955
01:00:33,327 --> 01:00:37,889
- For instance?
- Some time we'll spend a week
at the old Finney mansiףn...

956
01:00:37,965 --> 01:00:40,900
down by the tracks
and I'll go into detail.

957
01:00:40,968 --> 01:00:43,732
Right now,
I'd better get dressed.

958
01:00:45,072 --> 01:00:49,668
You know what?
I think you're worried.

959
01:00:49,743 --> 01:00:52,439
I think you're just as worried
as the rest of us.

960
01:00:52,513 --> 01:00:56,074
I've got everything I want.

961
01:01:14,602 --> 01:01:18,629
<i> Maybe you haven't got</i>
<i>everything you wanted after all.</i>

962
01:01:23,477 --> 01:01:28,312
<i> Maybe you haven't got</i>
<i>everything that you wanted after all.</i>

963
01:01:36,790 --> 01:01:39,281
- Your bet.
- How much you got in front of you?

964
01:01:39,360 --> 01:01:41,590
About $11,000.

965
01:01:41,662 --> 01:01:44,324
That's my bet.

966
01:01:44,398 --> 01:01:47,333
- Okay, what do you got?
- Ace high.

967
01:01:47,401 --> 01:01:50,097
- Your next?
- Jack.

968
01:01:50,170 --> 01:01:52,502
Nine. You win. Beer?

969
01:01:52,573 --> 01:01:54,973
Yeah, if you're
all out of champagne.

970
01:02:43,757 --> 01:02:47,955
<i>Ma! Just because she's going out</i>
<i>with Mr. Porter Hollingsway...</i>

971
01:02:48,028 --> 01:02:50,292
does she have to stay in the bathroom
for almost an hour?

972
01:02:50,364 --> 01:02:52,992
You oughtn't to run around like that.
You'll get consumption.

973
01:02:53,067 --> 01:02:55,228
Lora Mae, let your sister
get in the bathroom!

974
01:02:55,302 --> 01:02:58,396
After all, I've got a date,
too, a respectable date.

975
01:02:58,472 --> 01:03:00,633
- That's your sister you're talking about.
- I don't care.

976
01:03:00,708 --> 01:03:03,643
I think it's disgusting.
He's 35 if he's a day.

977
01:03:03,711 --> 01:03:05,872
I wish I was that
disgusting again.

978
01:03:05,946 --> 01:03:09,074
- Your sister knows what she's doing.
- They all know what they're doing.

979
01:03:09,149 --> 01:03:12,676
They're always going to wind up
being supervisors or buyers or something.

980
01:03:12,753 --> 01:03:15,313
Well, Porter Hollingsway
knows what he's doing too.

981
01:03:15,389 --> 01:03:18,415
Lora Mae, didn't you hear
what Ma said?

982
01:03:18,492 --> 01:03:21,552
And how do you think I feel
having my friends talk about my sister?

983
01:03:21,629 --> 01:03:24,257
Your sister's a decent girl,
like I hope you are.

984
01:03:24,331 --> 01:03:26,663
And there's nothing wrong
in going out with the boss...

985
01:03:26,734 --> 01:03:29,396
- if it'll bring a couple of bucks into the house.
- Nothing wrong?

986
01:03:29,470 --> 01:03:32,598
- No, nothing wrong.
- Then she'll wind up with
a steak dinner and that's all.

987
01:03:32,673 --> 01:03:34,766
Are you looking
for another smack?

988
01:03:34,842 --> 01:03:37,037
Ma, will you please
make her get out?

989
01:03:37,111 --> 01:03:41,275
- Oh, all right. Lora Mae...
- Yes, Mother?

990
01:03:41,348 --> 01:03:44,579
You don't own that bathroom, you know.
There's other people in this house.

991
01:03:44,652 --> 01:03:48,918
But you're such a quiet little thing, dear,
one never knows you're about.

992
01:03:48,989 --> 01:03:52,425
I still think it's disgusting.

993
01:03:52,493 --> 01:03:54,927
How do I look?

994
01:03:54,995 --> 01:03:57,259
If I was you,
I'd show more of what I got.

995
01:03:57,331 --> 01:04:00,562
- Maybe wear something with beads.
- What I got don't need beads.

996
01:04:00,634 --> 01:04:03,694
What's your new job gonna be,
something secret, like a spy?

997
01:04:03,771 --> 01:04:05,898
Something you can't
talk about in the office?

998
01:04:05,973 --> 01:04:08,271
All right, so I'm gonna disgrace
the fair name of Finney.

999
01:04:08,342 --> 01:04:10,537
Wait till it snows and throw me
out in the street.

1000
01:04:10,611 --> 01:04:13,637
I'm beginning to think your sister's right.
And to think a daughter of mine...

1001
01:04:13,714 --> 01:04:16,808
- How many payments are you
behind on that icebox?
- Not for all the iceboxes.

1002
01:04:16,884 --> 01:04:20,650
They can come and take it away, though heaven
knows it's one of the few joys I have in life.

1003
01:04:20,721 --> 01:04:23,155
They're not gonna take it away,
and I know what I'm doing.

1004
01:04:23,223 --> 01:04:25,623
Remember, you're my daughter
and a decent girl.

1005
01:04:25,693 --> 01:04:29,288
Come on, Ruby, lay off her.

1006
01:04:29,363 --> 01:04:31,831
- It's him.
- I guess so.

1007
01:04:31,899 --> 01:04:35,096
- Have you got everything? Where's your purse?
- Right there.

1008
01:04:35,169 --> 01:04:37,933
He's out in front
in a car a block long.

1009
01:04:38,005 --> 01:04:40,098
- Well, what are you waiting for?
- Relax.

1010
01:04:40,174 --> 01:04:42,267
He just blew his horn again.

1011
01:04:42,342 --> 01:04:45,402
- It ain't Gabriel. Relax.
- My nerves can't take this.

1012
01:04:45,479 --> 01:04:49,313
Lora Mae, what are you waiting for?

1013
01:04:49,383 --> 01:04:52,011
That's what I was waiting for.

1014
01:04:52,086 --> 01:04:54,452
Sadie, would you be good enough
to answer the door?

1015
01:04:54,521 --> 01:04:59,686
Well, my uniףn don't like me doin'
this kind of thing for free, but... okay.

1016
01:05:01,862 --> 01:05:05,764
Anybody wants me can come in
and get me. This ain't a drive-in.

1017
01:05:05,833 --> 01:05:07,892
Well, I never.

1018
01:05:10,904 --> 01:05:12,997
Hello, Sadie.

1019
01:05:13,073 --> 01:05:15,234
Hi, Porter.

1020
01:05:18,112 --> 01:05:20,546
- Good evening, Mr. Hollingsway.
- Good evening.

1021
01:05:20,614 --> 01:05:24,516
- I see you know Miss Dugan.
- He just didn't know my last name was Dugan.

1022
01:05:24,585 --> 01:05:28,385
- But I don't believe you know my mother,
Mrs. Finney. Mother...
- Pleased to meet you.

1023
01:05:28,455 --> 01:05:30,889
- How do you do?
- Won't you sit down?

1024
01:05:30,958 --> 01:05:34,553
Well, l... The table's reserved
for half past 7:00. It's after that now.

1025
01:05:34,628 --> 01:05:37,961
Yes, you are late, aren't you?
I won't be a minute. Just get my bag.

1026
01:05:38,031 --> 01:05:41,831
- Your bag is...
- It's a cold night out, ain't it?

1027
01:05:41,902 --> 01:05:44,200
Not bad. Uh...

1028
01:06:20,307 --> 01:06:22,775
- One of mine, right?
- Uh-huh.

1029
01:06:22,843 --> 01:06:25,903
<i>- Giant-sized with a super-freeze box, right?</i>
- Uh-huh.

1030
01:06:25,979 --> 01:06:28,277
How long you had it?

1031
01:06:28,348 --> 01:06:31,078
- Uh, h-how long they been on the market?
<i>- Mm, couple of years.</i>

1032
01:06:31,151 --> 01:06:33,312
- Uh, that was one of the first.
- Uh-huh.

1033
01:06:39,660 --> 01:06:44,723
- I wonder what's keepin' her?
- Giris always got things to do, they tell me.

1034
01:06:44,798 --> 01:06:50,566
- Why, there it is. How silly of me. Ready?
- We're late.

1035
01:06:50,637 --> 01:06:53,629
Good night, Mother, dear.
Don't wait up.

1036
01:06:53,707 --> 01:06:56,870
Thank you, Sadie, darling.
Good night.

1037
01:07:08,689 --> 01:07:13,319
- "Thank you, Sadie, darling."
- "Good night, Mother, dear. Don't wait up."

1038
01:07:13,393 --> 01:07:16,794
If a daughter of mine ever really talked
like that, I'd cut her tongue out.

1039
01:07:25,138 --> 01:07:27,265
Here you are, Mr. Hollingsway.

1040
01:07:27,341 --> 01:07:31,334
My, what a pretty shade of green.
What's it called?

1041
01:07:31,411 --> 01:07:33,572
Crטme de menthe.
Tastes like peppermint.

1042
01:07:33,647 --> 01:07:36,138
- It isn't too strong, is it?
- Wouldn't hurt a baby.

1043
01:07:37,484 --> 01:07:40,214
Well, I'll just
have to trust you.

1044
01:07:46,159 --> 01:07:48,252
Mmm. It's good.

1045
01:07:48,328 --> 01:07:51,525
Oh, my. When I think of all the
wonderful things that you know about...

1046
01:07:51,598 --> 01:07:54,863
- that I've never even heard of...
- Got a few years head start.

1047
01:07:54,935 --> 01:07:59,031
Now don't you go making yourself
out an old man, Mr. Hollingsway.

1048
01:07:59,106 --> 01:08:02,098
Let's make it Porter.

1049
01:08:02,175 --> 01:08:06,771
Why, the way I look at it, a man isn't
really grown up till, say, 35 at the least.

1050
01:08:06,847 --> 01:08:08,838
Yeah.

1051
01:08:11,184 --> 01:08:14,847
This is a very nice place. I've heard about it,
though, of course, I've never been.

1052
01:08:14,922 --> 01:08:17,015
I come here all the time.

1053
01:08:17,090 --> 01:08:20,116
With other young ladies you want to
talk to about new duties at the store?

1054
01:08:20,193 --> 01:08:22,286
Let's not talk business.

1055
01:08:22,362 --> 01:08:24,660
I thought that's what this dinner was for,
Mr. Hollingsway.

1056
01:08:24,731 --> 01:08:27,029
We'll get around to it.

1057
01:08:27,100 --> 01:08:29,398
You poor man. I suppose
you never get a chance to relax.

1058
01:08:29,469 --> 01:08:31,630
People always after you for things.

1059
01:08:31,705 --> 01:08:35,801
What do you do with yourself
after working hours, say, uh, nights?

1060
01:08:35,876 --> 01:08:38,310
I have my family
and my friends, of course.

1061
01:08:38,378 --> 01:08:41,404
- Boyfriends?
- Isn't that getting a little personal?

1062
01:08:41,481 --> 01:08:44,575
Oh, a girl like you,
I'll bet there's plenty. Who's out in front?

1063
01:08:44,651 --> 01:08:47,643
I don't happen to be
one of those giris...

1064
01:08:47,721 --> 01:08:50,053
that talks about her private life,
Mr. Hollingsway.

1065
01:08:50,123 --> 01:08:52,216
And what I do in my private life...

1066
01:08:52,292 --> 01:08:55,659
is my own personal business
and nobody else's.

1067
01:08:55,729 --> 01:08:58,527
- How about another drink?
- Oh, no, really. L...

1068
01:08:58,598 --> 01:09:01,658
<i>Why, it's Porter Hollingsway. Don't get up.</i>

1069
01:09:01,735 --> 01:09:04,533
- Hello, George. You here alone?
- With Rita, of course.

1070
01:09:04,604 --> 01:09:06,765
Funny, we called your house,
but you'd just left.

1071
01:09:06,840 --> 01:09:09,001
<i>- Addie's with us.</i>
- Addie?

1072
01:09:09,076 --> 01:09:12,443
<i>It was a last-minute idea. We figured</i>
<i>you'd probably have a previous engagement.</i>

1073
01:09:12,512 --> 01:09:15,845
- Whose idea, Addie's?
- As a matter of fact, now let me think...

1074
01:09:15,916 --> 01:09:18,578
- May I have a cigarette, please?
- Oh, here you are.

1075
01:09:18,652 --> 01:09:21,177
Oh, thank you.
Uh, thank you, Mr<i>...</i>

1076
01:09:21,254 --> 01:09:23,882
- Phipps. George Phipps.
- This is Miss Finney.

1077
01:09:23,957 --> 01:09:26,118
- How do you do?
- Hello, Miss Finney.

1078
01:09:26,193 --> 01:09:28,684
- Been here long?
- We just got here.

1079
01:09:28,762 --> 01:09:31,560
Didn't you see Rita and Addie go by?
They were a few steps ahead of me.

1080
01:09:31,631 --> 01:09:35,863
- Just now?
- Why, I'm sure they saw you, but
you probably weren't looking.

1081
01:09:35,936 --> 01:09:38,700
Not that I blame him. Say hello
on your way out, why don't you, hmm?

1082
01:09:38,772 --> 01:09:40,831
<i>- Yeah.</i>
- Love to.

1083
01:09:44,177 --> 01:09:46,771
You have such nice friends.

1084
01:09:46,847 --> 01:09:50,374
He's a schoolteacher.
He hasn't got a dime.

1085
01:09:50,450 --> 01:09:54,045
Oh. You were saying something
about another drink.

1086
01:09:54,121 --> 01:09:56,954
Mm, it's gettin' stuffy in here.
I want some air.

1087
01:10:45,839 --> 01:10:49,639
Weren't you out of cigarettes back there?
Didn't you ask George for one?

1088
01:10:49,709 --> 01:10:52,143
- Did I?
- You're smart.

1089
01:10:52,212 --> 01:10:54,271
- Thanks.
- Plenty smart.

1090
01:10:56,583 --> 01:11:00,781
- We gonna talk about business now?
- Let's look at the view.

1091
01:11:00,854 --> 01:11:03,345
- Miss Lipke is leaving next week.
- Yeah.

1092
01:11:03,423 --> 01:11:06,119
And if Miss Goldberg moves up,
you'll need a new assistant supervisor.

1093
01:11:06,193 --> 01:11:08,661
- Like flies around honey.
- Hmm?

1094
01:11:08,728 --> 01:11:11,196
You and your boyfriends.

1095
01:11:11,264 --> 01:11:15,792
- I thought we settled that.
- I want to talk about it some more.

1096
01:11:15,869 --> 01:11:18,463
What makes you so interested
in my boyfriends?

1097
01:11:18,538 --> 01:11:22,030
- What do you think?
- Which is the ashtray?

1098
01:11:27,881 --> 01:11:32,318
- I've got very definite ideas.
- Like what?

1099
01:11:32,385 --> 01:11:36,754
There's never been anybody
in particular. Nobody special.

1100
01:11:36,823 --> 01:11:38,984
Plenty that wanted to, I'll bet.

1101
01:11:39,059 --> 01:11:42,756
- What do you think?
- That you've been waiting for
that one guy to come along.

1102
01:11:42,829 --> 01:11:47,357
- I got very definite ideas.
- What's he got to be like, this one guy?

1103
01:11:47,434 --> 01:11:51,131
Someone who wants to marry me
more than anything else in the worid.

1104
01:11:53,773 --> 01:11:56,674
You sure got wrong ideas
about things.

1105
01:11:58,078 --> 01:12:02,037
They may be wrong,
but they're definite.

1106
01:12:02,115 --> 01:12:05,175
Well, tomorrow's another
working day. Shall we go?

1107
01:12:05,252 --> 01:12:07,345
Yeah.

1108
01:12:45,158 --> 01:12:47,490
Well, home again.

1109
01:12:47,561 --> 01:12:50,291
I want to thank you
for a lovely evening, Mr. Hollingsway.

1110
01:12:50,363 --> 01:12:52,456
That's all right.

1111
01:13:18,325 --> 01:13:22,989
Oh, now, look what I've done. My best nylons.

1112
01:13:23,063 --> 01:13:27,932
- Too bad.
- Oh, must have caught on a nail
or something at the restaurant.

1113
01:13:29,736 --> 01:13:31,761
I hope you don't mind
my bringing it up...

1114
01:13:31,838 --> 01:13:34,432
but could you remember about Miss Lipke
leaving and Miss Goldberg moving up?

1115
01:13:34,507 --> 01:13:36,634
What about tomorrow night?

1116
01:13:36,710 --> 01:13:39,201
- If you'd like.
- I'd like.

1117
01:13:39,279 --> 01:13:41,372
Half past 7:00.

1118
01:14:00,767 --> 01:14:03,998
Thank you again, Mr. Hollingsway,
for the lovely nylons.

1119
01:14:04,070 --> 01:14:06,595
- It wasn't really necessary.
- Forget it.

1120
01:14:09,442 --> 01:14:11,569
Uh, before we say good-bye...

1121
01:14:11,645 --> 01:14:15,376
l- I'd like to tell you that your friendship
has meant a great deal to me...

1122
01:14:15,448 --> 01:14:18,645
and our evenings together,
they've been wonderful.

1123
01:14:18,718 --> 01:14:20,777
And I'm just sorry that...

1124
01:14:22,589 --> 01:14:25,752
Well, good-bye.

1125
01:14:25,825 --> 01:14:27,918
Good-bye.

1126
01:14:38,104 --> 01:14:40,834
Oh, Mr. Hollingsway!

1127
01:14:43,076 --> 01:14:46,944
Oh, I'm terribly sorry.
How stupid of me.

1128
01:14:47,013 --> 01:14:49,573
After all my graceful speeches,
I forgot my nylons.

1129
01:14:49,649 --> 01:14:52,618
- They're in the back.
- I know.

1130
01:14:58,825 --> 01:15:00,918
Good night again.

1131
01:15:07,200 --> 01:15:09,327
Good-bye, Porter.

1132
01:15:56,583 --> 01:15:58,676
- That's all.
- Yes, sir.

1133
01:16:01,354 --> 01:16:03,481
It's gonna be a white Christmas.

1134
01:16:03,556 --> 01:16:06,650
That song, they tell me it made a million bucks
for the fella who wrote it.

1135
01:16:10,530 --> 01:16:13,260
This is the most beautiful house
I've ever seen.

1136
01:16:13,333 --> 01:16:17,793
- It's just everything anybody'd want.
- You name it, I got it.

1137
01:16:17,871 --> 01:16:20,840
- You were married once, weren't you?
- See if it's too sweet.

1138
01:16:24,010 --> 01:16:28,003
- Perfect. Is this her picture?
- My wife? I wouldn't even have
her fingerprints in the house.

1139
01:16:28,081 --> 01:16:31,312
- Then who's this?
- Somebody I know.

1140
01:16:31,384 --> 01:16:35,878
I bet I can guess... Addie Ross.

1141
01:16:35,955 --> 01:16:40,119
- That's right.
- So that's what she looks like.

1142
01:16:40,193 --> 01:16:43,629
You can't tell from that really.
It's only a picture.

1143
01:16:43,696 --> 01:16:46,130
She's beautiful all right.

1144
01:16:46,199 --> 01:16:48,394
She sort of looks like a queen,
doesn't she?

1145
01:16:48,468 --> 01:16:50,561
Like a queen ought to look.

1146
01:16:57,210 --> 01:16:59,337
I imagine you must be
very good friends.

1147
01:16:59,412 --> 01:17:03,143
I helped her with some investments.
She gave me this last Christmas.

1148
01:17:03,216 --> 01:17:05,343
Almost a year ago.

1149
01:17:05,418 --> 01:17:09,787
Yeah. Just never bothered
to put it away, I guess.

1150
01:17:20,633 --> 01:17:24,330
- Porter?
- You know how I feel about you.

1151
01:17:24,404 --> 01:17:26,463
How?

1152
01:17:31,444 --> 01:17:33,844
I'm only human, you know.

1153
01:17:33,913 --> 01:17:36,006
- I'm not so sure you are.
- No?

1154
01:17:36,082 --> 01:17:38,107
- No.
- Thanks.

1155
01:17:38,184 --> 01:17:40,277
- You're smart.
- So you told me.

1156
01:17:40,353 --> 01:17:42,446
- I'm smart, too, and I've been around.
- I'll bet.

1157
01:17:42,522 --> 01:17:44,956
It's an old act, you're good at it,
but you don't fool me.

1158
01:17:45,024 --> 01:17:49,120
- You're smart, all right, smarter than anybody.
- And I know all the answers.

1159
01:17:49,195 --> 01:17:51,459
Then answer this one...
why pick on me?

1160
01:17:51,531 --> 01:17:54,625
"I've been watching your work, Miss Finney,
and I think you're ready for advancement.

1161
01:17:54,701 --> 01:17:56,726
Let's have dinner
and talk it over."

1162
01:17:56,803 --> 01:17:59,704
There's a brand-new act for you.
It's got a beard a mile long.

1163
01:17:59,772 --> 01:18:04,766
I didn't ask you out. You asked me.
And why me? The woods are full of giris.

1164
01:18:04,844 --> 01:18:09,372
- Not like you.
- You can say it again, not like me.

1165
01:18:09,449 --> 01:18:12,941
- And they don't want what I want.
- All right, what do you want?

1166
01:18:13,019 --> 01:18:16,284
Not a $4.00-a-week raise.
I don't want a new car, a fur coat...

1167
01:18:16,356 --> 01:18:18,984
or a trip to Hawaii
on a solid-gold yacht.

1168
01:18:19,058 --> 01:18:23,392
You don't carry what I want in any
of your seven big stores, Mr. Hollingsway.

1169
01:18:26,132 --> 01:18:28,464
Name it.

1170
01:18:28,534 --> 01:18:31,401
I want to be in a sliver frame
on a piano.

1171
01:18:31,471 --> 01:18:33,735
My own piano
in my own house.

1172
01:18:33,806 --> 01:18:36,775
- You mean you want to get married.
- Does that make me a freak?

1173
01:18:36,843 --> 01:18:40,438
I've been married once, you know that,
and once is enough for a man like me.

1174
01:18:40,513 --> 01:18:43,914
- Maybe I'm just not the type.
- Maybe you just haven't found the right girl.

1175
01:18:43,983 --> 01:18:46,952
Living with somebody all the time.
I'm not easy to get along with.

1176
01:18:47,020 --> 01:18:50,080
I'm set in my ways, I want to do
what I want when I want.

1177
01:18:50,156 --> 01:18:52,283
Why, if it was just a question
of the right girl...

1178
01:18:52,358 --> 01:18:54,451
wouldn't any man in the worid
want to marry you?

1179
01:18:54,527 --> 01:18:57,826
Not if he thought
he could marry Addie Ross.

1180
01:19:00,033 --> 01:19:03,594
Maybe I don't know all the answers,
but I know some of them.

1181
01:19:46,813 --> 01:19:51,978
- It's late. I'd better be getting home.
- Okay if I call you a cab?

1182
01:19:52,051 --> 01:19:54,747
Beats walking in the snow.

1183
01:20:04,097 --> 01:20:07,658
<i>This is Porter Hollingsway. How long</i>
<i>before you can get a cab over to my house?</i>

1184
01:20:07,734 --> 01:20:12,865
Okay, hustle it along. And, say,
put the charge on my account. Yeah.

1185
01:20:12,939 --> 01:20:14,998
It'll be just a minute.

1186
01:20:19,078 --> 01:20:22,104
Sounds like you keep the cabs
pretty busy with this kind of thing.

1187
01:20:22,181 --> 01:20:26,049
The reason I keep an account is because
I do a lot of business with them, store business.

1188
01:20:26,119 --> 01:20:29,088
- Well, don't get mad.
- You just keep needling me.

1189
01:20:29,155 --> 01:20:33,091
I'd insist upon paying for that cab myself,
but I'm in no spot to be proud.

1190
01:20:33,159 --> 01:20:35,855
- From tomorrow on, I count the pennies.
- What's tomorrow?

1191
01:20:35,928 --> 01:20:38,294
- The day I start looking for a new job.
- I'm not gonna fire you.

1192
01:20:38,364 --> 01:20:40,730
- I'm gonna quit.
- What do you wanna do that for?

1193
01:20:40,800 --> 01:20:44,531
That's a silly question coming
from a man who knows all the answers.

1194
01:20:44,604 --> 01:20:47,266
None of the others quit.
Why should I, is that it?

1195
01:20:47,340 --> 01:20:51,299
Don't let it worry you, Porter. Maybe it's
just a new twist in the same old act.

1196
01:20:51,377 --> 01:20:53,470
There's the cab.

1197
01:20:53,546 --> 01:20:55,980
- I'll take you to the door.
- You stay where you are.

1198
01:20:57,950 --> 01:21:00,441
This time it's good-bye
and no kidding.

1199
01:21:00,520 --> 01:21:03,648
Maybe you're right, Porter.
Maybe I'm a fool.

1200
01:21:03,723 --> 01:21:07,215
But maybe you're
the biggest fool in the worid.

1201
01:21:25,978 --> 01:21:28,310
Lora Mae.

1202
01:21:57,043 --> 01:21:59,944
- Happy New Year!
- Happy New Year.

1203
01:22:00,012 --> 01:22:02,810
- Will you stand still?
- Oh, this dress ain't my type at all.

1204
01:22:02,882 --> 01:22:05,009
For one thing,
it's too high in the front.

1205
01:22:05,084 --> 01:22:07,814
If my best dress ain't good enough for you,
you can get out of it right now.

1206
01:22:07,887 --> 01:22:10,219
Just don't give me that
big sacrifice routine.

1207
01:22:10,289 --> 01:22:13,656
- You'd wear it yourself
if you had someplace to go.
- Okay, that does it.

1208
01:22:13,726 --> 01:22:16,718
- Take it off.
- It was Ma's idea for me to wear it, not yours.

1209
01:22:16,796 --> 01:22:18,991
It's still my dress
and you got 30 seconds to get out of it.

1210
01:22:19,065 --> 01:22:21,556
Just because it's New Year's Eve
and you haven't even got a date...

1211
01:22:21,634 --> 01:22:24,159
- You're gonna look silly running
round this kitchen stark naked.

1212
01:22:24,237 --> 01:22:26,364
- Ma!
- Ten seconds to go.

1213
01:22:26,439 --> 01:22:30,000
- Just because you got
Porter Hollingsway mad at you...
- Five seconds!

1214
01:22:30,076 --> 01:22:32,340
- Ma!
<i>- Lora Mae!</i>

1215
01:22:32,411 --> 01:22:35,141
Can't we have some peace in this house
even on New Year's Eve?

1216
01:22:35,214 --> 01:22:37,341
You got it mixed up
with Christmas.

1217
01:22:37,416 --> 01:22:39,543
New Year's Eve is when people
go back to killing each other.

1218
01:22:39,619 --> 01:22:42,053
Which reminds me,
I gotta go to work.

1219
01:22:42,121 --> 01:22:46,217
That's a fine way to see the new year in, serving
up champagne for Mrs. Addie Ross and friends.

1220
01:22:46,292 --> 01:22:49,693
It beats sitting alone
with a glass of stale beer.

1221
01:22:49,762 --> 01:22:52,060
Forget it, Sadie.
I didn't mean it the way it sounded.

1222
01:22:52,131 --> 01:22:56,158
I know. Tell you what, comes midnight,
I'll slip Porter Hollingsway a mickey.

1223
01:22:56,235 --> 01:22:58,726
- Don't bother.
- It's a pleasure. Night, kids.

1224
01:22:58,804 --> 01:23:01,830
- Happy New Year, Sadie.
- Is he goin' to be at the Addie Ross party?

1225
01:23:01,908 --> 01:23:04,035
That's what the invite says.

1226
01:23:04,110 --> 01:23:06,840
- She's expecting the pleasure of his company.
- How do you know?

1227
01:23:06,913 --> 01:23:11,043
Listen, when they hire Sadie Dugan
for a waitress, they submit a guest list.

1228
01:23:11,117 --> 01:23:13,415
- And Lora Mae could have been there too.
- Stop pickin' on her!

1229
01:23:13,486 --> 01:23:17,013
- Who's pickin' on her?
- You and Babe. You stop it
and make Babe stop it too.

1230
01:23:17,089 --> 01:23:19,853
Of all the time to quit a job,
just before Christmas with all the bills due...

1231
01:23:19,926 --> 01:23:22,121
and five months due on the icebox.

1232
01:23:22,195 --> 01:23:25,596
You got to make up your mind whether you
want your kids happy or your icebox paid up.

1233
01:23:25,665 --> 01:23:29,123
- Oh, not for all the iceboxes in the worid...
- Oh, relax.

1234
01:23:29,202 --> 01:23:31,363
Have a good time tonight
at the bingo party.

1235
01:23:31,437 --> 01:23:33,564
Gee, I wish you were
gonna be there.

1236
01:23:33,639 --> 01:23:36,369
- Happy New Year, Ruby.
- Happy New Year, Sadie.

1237
01:23:42,215 --> 01:23:45,241
- You sure you don't want to
come play bingo with me?
- Thanks, Ma.

1238
01:23:45,318 --> 01:23:49,220
- I'll be home before midnight.
- Oh, you don't have to on my account.
I'm going to bed early.

1239
01:23:49,288 --> 01:23:51,688
Well, I better go get dressed.

1240
01:24:20,586 --> 01:24:22,747
<i>- Hi, Lora Mae.</i>
- Hi, Nick.

1241
01:24:22,822 --> 01:24:25,848
- Babe ready yet?
- Unless she's beat her brains out
with a powder puff.

1242
01:24:25,925 --> 01:24:29,520
- Sit down. Give me a cigarette, huh?
- Sure.

1243
01:24:31,764 --> 01:24:34,358
Hey, how come you ain't dressed up
for New Year's Eve?

1244
01:24:34,433 --> 01:24:37,129
I am. I'm going to
a fancy dress ball.

1245
01:24:37,203 --> 01:24:40,001
Yeah? As what?

1246
01:24:40,072 --> 01:24:43,166
- A queen.
- A queen?

1247
01:24:43,242 --> 01:24:45,608
A queen in a silver frame.

1248
01:24:47,246 --> 01:24:49,612
I don't get it.

1249
01:24:49,682 --> 01:24:51,877
I'll go see what's keeping Babe.

1250
01:25:14,807 --> 01:25:16,968
<i>- Who are you?</i>
- Uh, l...

1251
01:25:17,043 --> 01:25:20,012
- Where's Miss Finney?
- Well, s-she'll be out in a minute, Mr. Hollingsway.

1252
01:25:20,079 --> 01:25:24,015
- We met somewheres?
- Not exactly, Mr. Hollingsway.
I work in your shipping room.

1253
01:25:24,083 --> 01:25:26,210
- You waitin' for Miss Finney?
- Yes, sir.

1254
01:25:26,285 --> 01:25:29,220
- What's your name?
- Nick. Uh, Nicholas Butler.

1255
01:25:29,288 --> 01:25:32,621
- We're just good friends,
kinda, Miss Finney and me.
- Mm.

1256
01:25:35,227 --> 01:25:38,993
But I worked in your shipping room
three years, Mr. Hollingsway.

1257
01:25:40,132 --> 01:25:42,225
Baboon Face...

1258
01:25:44,837 --> 01:25:48,068
- This is my sister, Babe.
- My real name's Georgiana.

1259
01:25:48,140 --> 01:25:50,404
<i>Oh, what do you say, Babe.</i>

1260
01:25:59,085 --> 01:26:01,610
Happy New Year, Mr. Hollingsway.

1261
01:26:05,691 --> 01:26:10,025
I thought Baboon Face was waiting for you.

1262
01:26:10,096 --> 01:26:12,394
He used to. I gave him to Babe.
He goes with the dress.

1263
01:26:12,465 --> 01:26:14,456
- Have you got another dress?
- Why?

1264
01:26:14,533 --> 01:26:17,525
- I want to take you to a party.
- Addie Ross's party?

1265
01:26:17,603 --> 01:26:19,901
- Yeah.
- Maybe she wouldn't like that.

1266
01:26:19,972 --> 01:26:22,065
She said she'd be delighted.

1267
01:26:22,141 --> 01:26:25,235
She must need another waitress.

1268
01:26:25,311 --> 01:26:29,213
I told her we had a date and not
to expect me if you'd made other plans.

1269
01:26:29,281 --> 01:26:34,116
We haven't got a date and I haven't made
any plans, so why don't you just run along.

1270
01:26:34,186 --> 01:26:36,279
We could go someplace else.

1271
01:26:36,355 --> 01:26:38,619
- No.
- Why not?

1272
01:26:38,691 --> 01:26:41,592
You know why not.

1273
01:26:41,660 --> 01:26:45,061
- These are for you.
- Thanks.

1274
01:26:45,131 --> 01:26:47,759
- Put 'em on.
- I'm not goin' anywhere.

1275
01:26:47,833 --> 01:26:49,960
You wouldn't want
to let 'em die.

1276
01:26:50,035 --> 01:26:52,435
I'll put 'em in the icebox.

1277
01:26:52,505 --> 01:26:54,632
The orchids ain't paid for either.

1278
01:27:06,052 --> 01:27:09,351
- I can't take it anymore.
- I thought we decided to leave it alone.

1279
01:27:09,422 --> 01:27:12,619
- It's worse not seeing you, knowing you're here.
- Maybe I ought to leave town.

1280
01:27:12,692 --> 01:27:15,525
Wonderin' about you, who you're with,
who you're lookin' at, who you're kissin'...

1281
01:27:15,595 --> 01:27:18,155
- Easy now.
- I can't sleep nights thinkin' about you.

1282
01:27:18,231 --> 01:27:21,428
So what?
What do I do about it...

1283
01:27:21,501 --> 01:27:24,129
start the same thing all over again
and wind up the same way?

1284
01:27:24,204 --> 01:27:26,331
And what about the way
I feel? My sleep?

1285
01:27:26,406 --> 01:27:28,772
But then I'm not even human, am I?
I'm just a great big act.

1286
01:27:28,842 --> 01:27:31,538
- You know what you're doin' to me.
- And you know all the answers.

1287
01:27:31,611 --> 01:27:33,704
I can't take it anymore.

1288
01:27:34,948 --> 01:27:37,109
Oh, what's the use, Porter?

1289
01:27:37,183 --> 01:27:39,276
Tell Addie Ross
it's the cook's night out...

1290
01:27:39,352 --> 01:27:41,582
and I had to stay home
with the icebox.

1291
01:27:46,760 --> 01:27:49,490
Okay.

1292
01:27:49,562 --> 01:27:52,258
Okay, you win.
I'll marry you.

1293
01:27:54,534 --> 01:27:58,561
How about it?

1294
01:28:06,646 --> 01:28:09,012
Thanks... for nothin'.

1295
01:28:09,082 --> 01:28:11,209
Now what kind
of an answer is that?

1296
01:28:12,786 --> 01:28:16,222
I don't know.
I just felt like it, that's all.

1297
01:28:16,289 --> 01:28:18,416
We'll do all right, kid.

1298
01:28:18,491 --> 01:28:21,392
We're startin' out where
it takes most marriages years to get...

1299
01:28:21,461 --> 01:28:24,328
out in the open,
no jokers, you'll see.

1300
01:28:24,397 --> 01:28:26,661
You've made a good deal, Lora Mae.

1301
01:28:26,733 --> 01:28:30,169
<i>Lora Mae, honey, if you want me,</i>
<i>I'll be over at the Callahans'playing...</i>

1302
01:28:30,236 --> 01:28:34,002
Happy New Year, Ma.
We're gonna get married.

1303
01:28:35,942 --> 01:28:38,638
Bingo.

1304
01:29:09,142 --> 01:29:11,804
Well, see you tonight at the club.

1305
01:30:07,901 --> 01:30:10,802
- George?
- Hello, there.

1306
01:30:10,870 --> 01:30:14,033
George. George, darling.

1307
01:30:14,107 --> 01:30:17,042
- Hey, what brings this on?
- Oh, George, I've got to know something.

1308
01:30:17,110 --> 01:30:19,806
- There's something I'll just die
if I don't know right away.
- Wait till I turn off...

1309
01:30:19,879 --> 01:30:23,610
No. No, don't. Don't ever turn it off,
that wonderful music.

1310
01:30:23,683 --> 01:30:26,049
- Have you been drinking?
- Tell me right away, George. Tell me the truth.

1311
01:30:26,119 --> 01:30:28,212
- About what?
- Why didn't you go fishing today?

1312
01:30:28,288 --> 01:30:30,381
Oh, the phone.

1313
01:30:30,456 --> 01:30:32,981
And you never dress up when there's
no school. Why the blue suit today?

1314
01:30:33,059 --> 01:30:35,152
Well, there's a little story
connected with that.

1315
01:30:35,228 --> 01:30:38,823
<i>Mrs. Phipps, you're</i>
<i>wanted on the telephone. It's her.</i>

1316
01:30:38,898 --> 01:30:41,799
- Who?
<i>- Whosis. The one with the husband.</i>

1317
01:30:41,868 --> 01:30:43,961
- Mrs. Manleigh.
- Tell her I'm not in.

1318
01:30:44,037 --> 01:30:46,631
She called you twice
this afternoon.

1319
01:30:46,706 --> 01:30:49,903
- Not if you don't want me to.
- Talk to her.

1320
01:30:49,976 --> 01:30:55,414
Hello? Hello, Mrs. Manleigh.
Yes, so I hear. I wasn't home. Turn it up.

1321
01:30:55,481 --> 01:30:57,540
<i>- I see.</i>

1322
01:30:57,617 --> 01:30:59,983
Now, look, Mrs. Manleigh...

1323
01:31:00,053 --> 01:31:02,385
that woman doesn't change the cheese
your husband manufactures...

1324
01:31:02,455 --> 01:31:04,889
why should she change
what I write?

1325
01:31:04,958 --> 01:31:07,051
No, I'm sorry.

1326
01:31:07,126 --> 01:31:10,391
I said I'm sorry.
I will not work tonight.

1327
01:31:10,463 --> 01:31:14,331
Because, Mrs. Manleigh, my husband
doesn't like me to work on weekends.

1328
01:31:14,400 --> 01:31:17,164
Yes, he's right here.

1329
01:31:17,236 --> 01:31:21,263
But he's not twisting my arm.
I made up my mind all by myself.

1330
01:31:21,341 --> 01:31:24,037
No. You'll have the copy Monday.

1331
01:31:24,110 --> 01:31:26,340
Good-bye, Mrs. Manleigh.

1332
01:31:26,412 --> 01:31:30,246
- Peace, it's wonderful.
- Answer my questions.

1333
01:31:30,316 --> 01:31:33,752
Well, that night, the night of the Big Wind,
I came home with some news.

1334
01:31:33,820 --> 01:31:37,722
You were preoccupied, so after
a couple of tries, I decided to skip it.

1335
01:31:37,790 --> 01:31:40,418
It was just that the high school
dramatics society...

1336
01:31:40,493 --> 01:31:42,791
decided to do <i>Twelfth Night</i>
and asked me to direct it.

1337
01:31:42,862 --> 01:31:46,298
The first rehearsal was today, and I thought
my blue suit was more appropriate...

1338
01:31:46,366 --> 01:31:48,561
- than a pair of wading boots...
- And Addie knew about it.

1339
01:31:48,634 --> 01:31:51,569
Which accounts for,
"If music be the fool of love... play on."

1340
01:31:51,637 --> 01:31:53,832
And on and on.

1341
01:31:59,979 --> 01:32:02,641
Good evening, Thomasino.

1342
01:32:02,715 --> 01:32:05,775
- Did Mr. Bishop call?
- Lady call up, leave this message.

1343
01:32:05,852 --> 01:32:08,184
- Mr. Bishop's secretary?
- Didn't say, ma'am.

1344
01:32:12,992 --> 01:32:15,085
<i>Mr. Bishop called to say...</i>

1345
01:32:15,161 --> 01:32:19,393
<i>he is very sorry</i>
<i>he will not be home tonight.</i>

1346
01:32:38,184 --> 01:32:40,311
And here are the results of the eighth...

1347
01:32:40,386 --> 01:32:42,479
the winner, number seven,
Hoop Skirt...

1348
01:32:42,555 --> 01:32:44,785
second, number three,
Penny Wise...

1349
01:32:44,857 --> 01:32:47,087
third, number six, Pound Foolish.

1350
01:32:47,160 --> 01:32:50,061
Hoop Skirt paid 60...

1351
01:32:52,565 --> 01:32:55,762
You ought to use a walkie-talkie.
It don't make so much noise.

1352
01:32:55,835 --> 01:32:58,827
That was the last race.
Sadie's right. That track's crooked.

1353
01:32:58,905 --> 01:33:02,170
It isn't the track, it's the horses.
They fix things up amongst themselves.

1354
01:33:02,241 --> 01:33:05,301
How come Porter's
so late tonight?

1355
01:33:05,378 --> 01:33:09,007
- Want a drink?
- Some of that green peppermint stuff.

1356
01:33:09,082 --> 01:33:12,848
Crטme de menthe.
I can't stand it. Never could.

1357
01:33:12,919 --> 01:33:15,114
I love it.

1358
01:33:15,188 --> 01:33:18,521
It's 7:30.
He's never been this late.

1359
01:33:18,591 --> 01:33:22,857
Ma, Porter may not be home at all.

1360
01:33:22,929 --> 01:33:26,524
- You mean tonight?
- Any night. I think he's gone away for good.

1361
01:33:26,599 --> 01:33:30,695
- With somebody else? I don't believe it.
- I do.

1362
01:33:30,770 --> 01:33:33,796
Porter would never leave you for good,
and not for another woman.

1363
01:33:33,873 --> 01:33:36,307
- Why not?
- Because he's in love with you.

1364
01:33:36,375 --> 01:33:38,843
- What?
- Because he's just plain crazy in love with you.

1365
01:33:38,911 --> 01:33:42,813
- Are you out of your mind?
- I thought I heard soft voices in here.

1366
01:33:42,882 --> 01:33:46,545
- Hello, Porter.
- What's the fight about this time...
furs, jewelry or cash?

1367
01:33:46,619 --> 01:33:50,316
- My children and me never fight.
- Fix me a drink, will you? I'm tired.

1368
01:33:50,389 --> 01:33:55,326
And the reason we never fight bein' my children
know that I know what I'm talkin' about.

1369
01:33:58,731 --> 01:34:03,327
Maybe your fatherJoe Finney
wasn't exactly a saint, may he rest in peace...

1370
01:34:03,402 --> 01:34:06,064
but I learned about men from him.

1371
01:34:19,585 --> 01:34:22,019
- Too much soda.
- No more so than usual.

1372
01:34:22,088 --> 01:34:25,114
I'm too tired to play with it tonight.
I wanna drink it.

1373
01:34:27,660 --> 01:34:30,720
Addie Ross left town today
and took somebody's husband with her.

1374
01:34:30,796 --> 01:34:33,230
- Yeah?
- You seem real excited about it...

1375
01:34:33,299 --> 01:34:35,426
like I told you
we were having lamb for dinner.

1376
01:34:35,501 --> 01:34:38,368
What do you want me to do,
sue somebody? I'm tired.

1377
01:34:38,437 --> 01:34:40,530
I figured you might be
the lucky boy.

1378
01:34:40,606 --> 01:34:42,801
Then it must have broke your heart
when I walked in here.

1379
01:34:42,875 --> 01:34:44,968
Funny you should
mention my heart.

1380
01:34:45,044 --> 01:34:48,036
So you figured
I ran away with Addie Ross.

1381
01:34:48,114 --> 01:34:51,083
How'd it feel?
You don't have to tell me. I can tell you.

1382
01:34:51,150 --> 01:34:53,277
You ought to go on
<i>Information Please.</i>

1383
01:34:53,352 --> 01:34:58,085
So what? I got mine.
That's what you thought to yourself.

1384
01:34:58,157 --> 01:35:01,615
You ought to get a concessiףn at
some carnival. You're a regular mind reader.

1385
01:35:01,694 --> 01:35:04,288
<i>Three years of playing the good wife.</i>
<i>Here's where I cash in.</i>

1386
01:35:04,363 --> 01:35:09,062
Here comes the payoff.
That's what you thought.

1387
01:35:09,135 --> 01:35:11,933
I've been a good wife.
The best wife your money could buy.

1388
01:35:12,004 --> 01:35:16,998
- Strictly cash and carry.
- Isn't that what you wanted?
Isn't that what you told me?

1389
01:35:17,076 --> 01:35:20,477
"Out in the open.
You made a good deal, kid."

1390
01:35:20,546 --> 01:35:22,912
Did you ever stop to think, Porter,
that in over three years...

1391
01:35:22,982 --> 01:35:25,507
there's one word we've never said
to each other, even in fun?

1392
01:35:25,585 --> 01:35:28,247
To you, I'm a cash register.
You can't love a cash register.

1393
01:35:28,321 --> 01:35:30,789
And I'm part of your inventory.
You can't love that either.

1394
01:35:30,856 --> 01:35:34,519
- I asked you to marry me
because I was crazy about you.
- You didn't even ask me!

1395
01:35:34,594 --> 01:35:37,119
I've been a good husband.
You got everything you want.

1396
01:35:37,196 --> 01:35:39,596
If you'd only asked me, if you'd only
made me feel like a woman...

1397
01:35:39,665 --> 01:35:42,259
- instead of a piece of merchandise.
- Did you give me a chance to?

1398
01:35:42,335 --> 01:35:44,826
All you ever showed me
was your price tag.

1399
01:35:49,275 --> 01:35:53,109
You better get dressed.
We're meeting the others at half past 8:00.

1400
01:35:55,281 --> 01:35:57,374
I'll be ready when you are.

1401
01:36:15,868 --> 01:36:18,359
- She walks in beauty like the night.
- Hello, George.

1402
01:36:18,437 --> 01:36:21,031
Of cloudless climes
and starry skies...

1403
01:36:21,107 --> 01:36:23,302
and all that's good of dark...

1404
01:36:23,376 --> 01:36:27,176
- You're the most dreamy thing
I've ever hated at sight.
- Thanks so much.

1405
01:36:27,246 --> 01:36:29,714
<i>- How are the martinis?</i>
- Very high and dry.

1406
01:36:29,782 --> 01:36:32,216
- Let me bring you up to date.
- No, thanks.

1407
01:36:32,285 --> 01:36:34,685
- Not drinking?
- Not at the moment.

1408
01:36:34,754 --> 01:36:39,157
Say, how long a wait do you suppose before
Brad comes sliding down the banister?

1409
01:36:39,225 --> 01:36:42,388
- A rough idea.
- He's... not here.

1410
01:36:44,397 --> 01:36:46,524
What do you mean
he's not here?

1411
01:36:46,599 --> 01:36:49,329
Brad's not here.

1412
01:36:49,402 --> 01:36:53,065
There was a message when I got home
saying he wouldn't be back tonight.

1413
01:36:57,576 --> 01:37:00,545
Well, perhaps you'd rather
not go without him.

1414
01:37:00,613 --> 01:37:02,774
- Why not?
- Well, uh...

1415
01:37:02,848 --> 01:37:05,180
Then how about having just
one with us before we leave?

1416
01:37:05,251 --> 01:37:07,344
Thanks. I feel fine just as I am.

1417
01:37:07,420 --> 01:37:10,912
Oh, a tiny one, for medicinal purposes
against the night air, huh?

1418
01:37:10,990 --> 01:37:15,359
- She doesn't want one, George.
- Well, then, uh, shall we?

1419
01:37:43,122 --> 01:37:46,216
- Sure you don't want a drink?
- Sure.

1420
01:37:49,662 --> 01:37:52,563
You know who that guy is?
A bookie.

1421
01:37:52,631 --> 01:37:56,123
All the barbershops and saloons
in town dancing with my wife.

1422
01:37:56,202 --> 01:37:59,137
- He came over and asked very politely.
- She'd dance with anybody.

1423
01:37:59,205 --> 01:38:01,332
She waited to see
if you had any objections.

1424
01:38:01,407 --> 01:38:03,432
I wouldn't object
if a chimpanzee asked her.

1425
01:38:03,509 --> 01:38:06,273
- Then you've got no right to complain.
- Oh, I've got no complaints.

1426
01:38:06,345 --> 01:38:09,143
I'm happyJoe from Kokomo.
Greatest little wife in the worid.

1427
01:38:09,215 --> 01:38:11,479
Fine home. Fine friends.
Everybody loves me.

1428
01:38:11,550 --> 01:38:14,781
- Oh, why don't you stop acting like a spoiled baby?
- Everybody loves Porter.

1429
01:38:14,854 --> 01:38:16,981
I'm fed up listening
to your waa-waa-waa.

1430
01:38:17,056 --> 01:38:19,957
You're always talking about being
such a man. You don't even act grown up.

1431
01:38:20,025 --> 01:38:22,858
- What are you gettin' sore about?
- You. You're so stupid.

1432
01:38:22,928 --> 01:38:27,297
- Now wait a minute!
- Have you any idea how much
Lora Mae's in love with you?

1433
01:38:27,366 --> 01:38:30,767
- No, how much?
- So much she's afraid to tell you,
afraid you'd laugh at her.

1434
01:38:30,836 --> 01:38:33,327
Me laugh? She couldn't say it
with a straight face.

1435
01:38:33,406 --> 01:38:36,341
Lora Mae in love with me?
It's all she can do to wait it out.

1436
01:38:36,409 --> 01:38:39,003
- Wait it out?
- Yeah, like an annuity till it matures.

1437
01:38:39,078 --> 01:38:42,104
Like a slot machine till it pays off.
That's what she's waitin' for.

1438
01:38:42,181 --> 01:38:46,174
A chance to call it off, to collect.
"The end of the line. Fares, please."

1439
01:38:46,252 --> 01:38:49,422
Don't tell me about love
and Lora Mae.

1440
01:38:49,555 --> 01:38:52,718
Oh, George.

1441
01:38:58,264 --> 01:39:00,528
There's a fine, relaxed
atmosphere at this table...

1442
01:39:00,599 --> 01:39:02,897
- as if there were a body hidden under it.
- I'm sorry.

1443
01:39:02,968 --> 01:39:05,129
Oh, I was only kidding.

1444
01:39:05,204 --> 01:39:07,968
What was it you called Addie
down at the pier... the dear departed?

1445
01:39:08,040 --> 01:39:11,999
Maybe that's who's under the table,
only it's Brad.

1446
01:39:12,077 --> 01:39:16,514
Uh, Deborah, why are you letting all this
nice, cold champagne fizz itself to death?

1447
01:39:16,582 --> 01:39:18,709
It sounds like one of
your quotations, Professor.

1448
01:39:18,784 --> 01:39:20,877
Can you give me something
fitting for the occasiףn?

1449
01:39:20,953 --> 01:39:24,150
Well, why not make up your own?
It's more fun.

1450
01:39:24,223 --> 01:39:27,659
I don't understand this conversation
at all. How drunk am I?

1451
01:39:30,996 --> 01:39:33,590
- Thank you very much, Mrs. Hollingsway.
- Let's do it again sometime.

1452
01:39:33,666 --> 01:39:37,261
- And thank you, Mr. Hollingsway.
- Yeah.

1453
01:39:37,336 --> 01:39:39,201
He seems pleasant enough.
Who is he?

1454
01:39:39,271 --> 01:39:41,535
A business associate
of my mother's.

1455
01:39:41,607 --> 01:39:43,939
He's a bookie.
Your mother bets with him.

1456
01:39:44,009 --> 01:39:46,705
Will everyone excuse me, please?
I think I'd like to leave.

1457
01:39:46,779 --> 01:39:49,179
- I'll drive you, Deborah.
- I'd rather go by myself, if you don't mind.

1458
01:39:49,248 --> 01:39:51,011
- What's goin' on here?
- Shut up.

1459
01:39:51,083 --> 01:39:53,916
- Why not spend the night with us, Debby?
- Thanks just the same.

1460
01:39:53,986 --> 01:39:57,786
- Will somebody tell me what this is all about?
- Later. I'll tell you later.

1461
01:39:57,857 --> 01:40:00,018
- Don't you know, Porter?
<i>- No.</i>

1462
01:40:00,092 --> 01:40:02,890
- Let's go for a little walk.
- No. I want to tell Porter what he doesn't know.

1463
01:40:02,962 --> 01:40:05,954
I want to say it out loud.
The reason I want to go home, Porter...

1464
01:40:06,031 --> 01:40:08,761
- is because I've been spoiling everybody's fun.
<i>- Don't be silly, Deb...</i>

1465
01:40:08,834 --> 01:40:12,565
I've tried hard to make believe the way you do,
Porter, but I'm not as much of a man as you are.

1466
01:40:12,638 --> 01:40:16,267
<i>- I can't anymore.</i>
- Make believe about what?

1467
01:40:16,342 --> 01:40:19,038
Don't you know by now?
You're not as smart as I thought, Porter.

1468
01:40:19,111 --> 01:40:22,569
- You want it in so many words? All right, then.
<i>- Deborah...</i>

1469
01:40:22,648 --> 01:40:26,106
My husband has run away
with Addie Ross.

1470
01:40:27,720 --> 01:40:30,655
Please, nobody get up.
Good night.

1471
01:40:31,724 --> 01:40:33,817
- Sit down.
- Porter, please.

1472
01:40:33,893 --> 01:40:35,952
- Sit down for a moment.
- Let her go, Porter.

1473
01:40:36,028 --> 01:40:38,053
You keep out of it.
Everyone else too.

1474
01:40:38,130 --> 01:40:40,530
Just for a minute?

1475
01:40:43,235 --> 01:40:47,569
Brad didn't run away
with Addie Ross. I did.

1476
01:40:50,175 --> 01:40:53,008
But how? You're here.

1477
01:40:53,078 --> 01:40:56,309
A man can change his mind,
can't he?

1478
01:41:08,561 --> 01:41:13,464
- Porter, you're quite a guy.
- Thanks.

1479
01:41:13,532 --> 01:41:15,466
She'd have known
in the morning anyway.

1480
01:41:15,534 --> 01:41:19,095
She'd have had a tough night.
She's just a kid.

1481
01:41:20,873 --> 01:41:23,000
Dance with me, George.

1482
01:41:25,611 --> 01:41:29,342
Rita, do you mind
just another minute?

1483
01:41:31,417 --> 01:41:35,945
Okay, you got it. They all heard me say
I ran away with another woman.

1484
01:41:36,021 --> 01:41:40,321
You've got everything you need.
You can take me for everything you'll ever want.

1485
01:41:43,729 --> 01:41:45,822
Like always, Porter...

1486
01:41:45,898 --> 01:41:49,664
when you start knocking on that
brandy bottle, you'll come up with anything.

1487
01:41:49,735 --> 01:41:51,669
I guess I stopped listening.

1488
01:41:51,737 --> 01:41:56,731
'Cause if you said something,
I just didn't hear it.

1489
01:42:00,913 --> 01:42:03,074
Why don't everybody dance?

1490
01:42:15,494 --> 01:42:17,724
Lora Mae.

1491
01:42:21,400 --> 01:42:24,494
You big gorilla.

1492
01:42:24,570 --> 01:42:27,164
Let's... dance?

1493
01:42:50,629 --> 01:42:54,497
<i>Heigh-ho. Good night, everybody.</i>

